<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / Lang move hits Scottish Nuclear
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, yesterday dealt a blow to Scottish
Nuclear's commercial strategy by deferring a decision on whether to approve
construction of a dry store for spent fuel at the Torness power station in
East Lothian.
Mr Lang said he would wait until the Department of the Environment finished
the review of radioactive waste strategy announced by Mr John Gummer, the
environment secretary, last month. The review, which will feed into the
overall nuclear review, will consider whether Britain should have a single
dry store for nuclear waste or stores at individual plants.
The review could delay approval for another year.
Last night Mr Robin Jeffrey, chief executive of the government-owned
Scottish Nuclear (SNL), called Mr Lang's announcement 'deeply
disappointing'. It would set back SNL's progress towards becoming fully
commercial, he said, and open up 'a totally irrelevant question'.
The dry store involves keeping spent nuclear fuel on the site of a power
station to let its radioactivity decline naturally rather than sending it
for more expensive reprocessing to British Nuclear Fuels' Thorp plant at
Sellafield, Cumbria.
If SNL built dry stores at both Torness and its Hunterston plant in Ayrshire
it would cut its operating costs by Pounds 45m a year. It has a target
cost-reduction figure of Pounds 100m a year. SNL has indicated that the
policy was favoured by the Scottish Office.
SNL had hoped to begin building the Pounds 80m-Pounds 100m dry store in late
summer for completion in just over two years.
</TEXT>
