<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / No answers at VAT gripeline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An attempt by HM Customs &amp; Excise to boost its caring image ran into
embarrassing early difficulties yesterday as the agency tried to unveil
details of an initiative designed to show its new-found helpfulness to
business.
The department said that from Monday companies would be able to gripe over
the telephone about their concerns in handling value added tax.
But in an omen of things to come, the agency said yesterday that it was
unable to provide further information such as the number or type of calls it
expected to receive because all the relevant officials were out of the
office.
After failing to raise any officials yesterday an exasperated press officer
said: 'I think they took advantage of the bank holiday and are not back
yet.'
The 'business-views hotline' will be open for three months for ideas on ways
to make VAT more 'user-friendly for business'.
Businesses hoping for proof that Customs staff are human will be
disappointed - the service will be in the form of recorded messages.
The department hopes that businesses will use the telephone to make
recommendations on improvements to the VAT system. Last month consultants
completed a survey of 1,000 businesses for Customs &amp; Excise to judge how it
could improve its quality of service, fulfil its commitments and keep
compliance requirements to a minimum.
One piece of good news is that rather than try to cash in on the
premium-rate charges often levied on recorded messages, the department has
arranged for calls to be free, on 0800 132384.
</TEXT>
