<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / TUC marshals cash for adverts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Trades Union Congress is co-ordinating a Pounds 100,000 advertising
campaign to urge voters in next week's European parliamentary elections to
back candidates who support the social chapter of the Maastricht treaty.
The advertisements are being paid for by unions which have political funds
but are not affiliated to the Labour party.
The bulk of the campaign's finance is from Unison, the public service union.
Another important contributor is the IRSF, the tax officers' union.
The TUC said last night that the unions involved were not calling on voters
to back Labour or any other political party.
It said Britain was alone among European Union countries in opposing legal
rights which made 'workers safer, more secure and more effective at work'.
The campaign is aimed at women voters. It suggests that the government is
opposing 10 ways under EU legislation to protect and improve the conditions
of female workers.
The TUC said: 'We are not endorsing Labour but we are saying that the views
of candidates on the social chapter ought to be of paramount importance on
who people vote for.
'We would expect all Labour candidates to back the social chapter. We think
most Liberal Democrats probably would. We think some Conservatives might,
despite the party's official line at national level. We don't know the
attitude of the Greens, the nationalists and the other parties in the
election.'
The TUC has taken legal advice to avoid any charge by government ministers
that unions are interfering in the European elections and misusing their
political funds for that purpose.
The TUC co-ordinated a similar campaign during the 1989 European
parliamentary elections, when it urged voters to vote for candidates who
backed workers' rights.
</TEXT>
