<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / Fresh row erupts over London radio
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shareholders in London Broadcasting Company have called for the licence of
its successor, London News Radio, to be revoked before the company even
begins broadcasting.
Lawyers representing Chelverton Investments, which controlled LBC until it
went into receivership, have written to the Radio Authority saying the two
London commercial speech-based services should be re-advertised.
SJ Berwin, the lawyers, say they want either to hear within seven days that
the licence will be revoked or to receive reasons why the authority has
decided not to revoke it.
If the reply is not satisfactory, the lawyers say they will advise their
clients of their right to apply for judicial review of the authority's
decision.
The row over the London commercial radio licences has blown up again because
of the announcement last week that Reuters Holdings, the news and
information group, is proposing to acquire LNR, the Guinness Mahon-backed
company which was awarded the licence last September in preference to LBC.
Reuters was part of the London Radio Company, another unsuccessful applicant
for the two franchises.
Before the Reuters plan to buy LNR for Pounds 5m, LNR had already acquired
the assets of LBC from the receivers.
Chelverton, whose main investors include Mr John Porter, son of the
controversial Conservative politician Dame Shirley Porter, clearly hopes to
persuade the LBC receivers and other applicants for the London licences to
join in a judicial-review application.
Chelverton claims through its lawyers that, before the Reuters announcement,
LNR had been unable to raise its financing. LNR said it had been well
advanced in putting together a syndicate to fund the station when it
received 'an offer it couldn't refuse'.
Chelverton argues that the licence should be revoked under the 1990
Broadcasting Act because the 'nature and characteristics' of LNR are now
completely different from the time of the licence award. Apart from the
proposed acquisition by Reuters, Guinness Mahon had failed to comply with a
statement in the LNR application that it would issue shares in LNR by way of
a private placement.
'The consequence of the acquisition of LNR by Reuters is that the licence
will be held by an entity which, when the statutory scheme for the award of
the licence was followed, was unsuccessful,' the letter to the Radio
Authority says.
</TEXT>
