<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / Halifax about to report fresh house price fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
First signs that the pace of the housing market recovery may be faltering
are expected to emerge this week when Halifax building society announces
that house prices fell in May.
The society's latest housing figures are expected to be published tomorrow.
They represent the second successive month in which Halifax, Britain's
largest mortgage lender, has reported a fall in prices compared with the
previous month.
The decline in the past two months has coincided with the introduction of
tax increases in April. There have been fears that the increases could
inhibit returning consumer confidence.
Signals from the housing market remain very mixed. Nationwide, Britain's
second-largest building society, said yesterday that according to its
mortgage figures house prices had risen by 1.4 per cent in May compared with
the previous month.
Mr Brian Davis, Nationwide's operations director, said: 'May is
traditionally a strong month for the housing market and the relatively large
rise in prices recorded should be seen in that context.' The average price
of a home had risen by 3.3 per cent to Pounds 54,617 during the previous
three months.
But Mr Davis agreed that 'recent indicators of market activity have been
mixed'.
He said: 'The underlying strengthening of the market which began in the
spring of last year is likely to be maintained, but progress is steady
rather than spectacular and heavily dependent on local conditions.
'The underlying trend over recent months has been broadly flat though prices
continue to show positive gains compared with the same period last year.'
Halifax had been prepared to regard a 0.2 per cent month-on-month price fall
in April as a blip but has become more worried at a second successive
monthly decline.
As a result it is expected to warn that its forecast of an average 5 per
cent price rise this year is less likely to be achieved. Nevertheless, it
still expects to see some small increase.
It is likely to wait for three or four months of falling prices before
revising its forecast. It believes that it is still too early to determine
the outcome of April's tax increases on housing market confidence although
it is concerned that the rise in sales by estate agents may also be
faltering a little.
The Halifax house prices are seasonally adjusted, unlike Nationwide's
survey. Halifax also uses a larger sample of mortgage loans.
</TEXT>
