<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / Imro discipline system outlined
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Imro, the self-regulatory body for the fund management industry, is to have
more scope to explain the reasoning behind disciplinary actions against its
members.
The move will come as part of the new disciplinary regime which will take
effect for all cases opened after August 1.
Issuing a statement on its disciplinary policy yesterday, Imro said that it
wanted to bring greater openness into the process.
Its statement sets out the four principles underlying the system, and the
considerations - such as the number of investors suffering losses, and
whether previous warnings were given - which affect the penalties imposed.
This is the first time a self-regulatory organisation has published such a
comprehensive statement of its disciplinary process - although earlier this
year Lautro, the regulator for the life insurance industry, issued a
statement warning life offices that, as a matter of policy, rule breaches
un-covered in the second round of routine inspection visits would attract
more severe penalties.
Imro also published yesterday a guidance note setting new minimum standards
on how unit trust managers should deal with pricing errors and compensate
investors significantly affected.
</TEXT>
