<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / Union chief wants unopposed crowning of Blair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The leader of one of Britain's biggest unions last night called on other
possible leadership candidates to follow Mr Gordon Brown's example and not
to stand against Mr Tony Blair, the favourite for the job.
'They should take a leaf out of Gordon's book,' said Mr Bill Jordan,
president of the AEEU engineering and electrical union. 'This is an act of
true statesmanship, true leadership, bringing the party together, showing
the country what is needed.'
Mr Jordan's call is likely to be echoed by other union leaders who believe
Mr Blair is virtually unstoppable - and there is therefore little point in
proceeding with an expensive election.
However, union leaders on the centre-left believe Mr Blair must be
challenged if only to ensure that a real debate can be held on the future
policy direction of the party. Many of them believe that Mrs Margaret
Beckett is now the only possible serious challenger.
Some union leaders fear that if Mr Blair wins a landslide victory as an
uncompromising moderniser he may attempt to reduce the power of the unions
in the Labour party.
Others are confident that Mr Blair supports the party's commitment to full
employment and the introduction of a national minimum wage. They also
believe he would not wish to re-open the controversial issue of the role of
the unions in the Labour party this side of the next general election.
Last night a spokesman for Mr Brown said that Mr Blair had agreed to back
the employment agenda outlined by Mr Brown in his recent speeches.
Union leaders on the centre-left are becoming reconciled to the prospect of
Mr Blair as leader - but they remain determined to uphold their authority in
the party and hold him to Labour's current economic policies.
</TEXT>
