<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / Leadership Contest: Painful decision of a friend and
pragmatist
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It was always the most likely outcome. After three weeks of agonising Mr
Gordon Brown has accepted that he cannot become leader of the Labour party -
at least this time round.
Mr Brown's fulsome statement of support for Mr Tony Blair, his main rival on
the party's ascendant modernist wing, is in line with their longstanding
political alliance.
It also underlines the continuing friendship between the two men, although
their relationship has been strained by Mr Blair's emergence as the runaway
leadership favourite.
Most of all, however, Mr Brown's announcement reflects his reluctant
acceptance of the Labour party's judgment that Mr Blair looks more likely to
win a general election.
It was a painful decision for a man who has devoted his adult life to the
Labour party, and who was regarded until recently as a more heavyweight
figure than Mr Blair.
Mr Brown, shadow chancellor, has borne the brunt of Labour's determination
to avoid damaging spending commitments before the next election. His
handling of the key economics portfolio has avoided the spending traps that
cost Labour dear at the 1992 election - but left him looking mean and
cautious to the party rank and file.
By contrast, Mr Blair, shadow home secretary, has built a reputation for
common sense and moderation with an effective attack on government law and
order policies.
Mr Brown's friends said he wanted to avoid a battle with Mr Blair which
could have done 'enormous damage' to the winner's hopes of defeating the
Tories in the next general election.
They admitted that he was trailing Mr Blair among constituencies and union
members, but claimed that support was equally split among backbench MPs,
shadow ministers and union leaders.
One close friend said: 'He believes he could have beaten Tony over the six
weeks of the campaign, but it would have been too damaging to the party.'
Much of this was taken with a pinch of salt by supporters of rival
candidates, who believe that Mr Blair has established an almost unassailable
lead in all sections of the party.
There was also some irritation at the timing of the announcement, which will
inevitably detract from coverage of Labour's European election campaign. One
MP said acidly: 'I thought the agreement that no-one would comment on the
leadership covered withdrawals from the race as well as campaign
statements.'
The mood of the party was more accurately expressed by Mr Donald Dewar,
shadow social security secretary, who was a prominent supporter of Mr Brown.
Mr Dewar, who will now switch his support to Mr Blair, said the decision
would remove uncertainty and enhance Mr Brown's position and stature in the
party.
It will certainly do that. As part of a deal with Mr Blair, Mr Brown has
been guaranteed the job of shadow chancellor until the next election, and
chancellor if Labour wins.
That was expected. But he will also have control of Labour's wider economic
policy, including issues such as business competitiveness and social
justice.
This wider brief will make Mr Brown by far the most influential member of Mr
Blair's team. If it works, it could promote a cohesive economic approach
across the shadow cabinet. But it could also lead to clashes with other
shadow ministers, including Mr John Prescott, employment spokesman, and Mr
Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary.
The two men, both seen as traditionalists, have a difficult relationship
with Mr Brown and there have been angry arguments about the development of
economic policy.
Both remain potential candidates for either the leadership or deputy
leadership, with Mrs Margaret Beckett, the traditionalist acting leader, and
Mr Jack Cunningham, the rightwing shadow foreign secretary.
Labour MPs said all four were still considering their positions, although Mr
Cunningham was regarded as highly unlikely to risk contesting either post.
Mr Cook is being wooed by Mr Blair's camp, which believes that his support
would remove any lingering doubts about the outcome of the election.
Mrs Beckett is widely expected to stand for re-election as deputy leader,
possibly as part of a balanced left/right ticket with Mr Blair.
Mr Prescott's friends say he is determined to stand for one of the
leadership posts, if only to force the modernists to debate the party's
future before Mr Blair is crowned leader.
Mr Prescott is unlikely to defeat either Mr Blair or Mrs Beckett, but his
standing might be strengthened if he were seen to have prevented a ritual
anointment of the new leader.
For Mr Brown, the immediate battle is over. He will work for Mr Blair in the
knowledge that victory for the shadow home secretary would leave the party's
modernists in virtually unchallenged control.
But if the battle is over, the war is not. If Mr Blair won the leadership
but lost the general election his hold on the job would be vulnerable to
challenge within three years.
If Mr Blair won the election he could be Labour leader for a decade. But at
43, Mr Brown could be in the party's top ranks for another 20 years. He
knows that his time may come.
</TEXT>
