<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / Unions see Beckett as only challenger to Blair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Union leaders believe Mr Tony Blair is virtually unstoppable in the election
for the next leader of the Labour party - with Mrs Margaret Beckett as the
only possible serious challenger if she decides to run.
Mr Bill Jordan, president of the AEEU craft union, said last night that Mr
Gordon Brown had been attracting a good deal of union support. But he added
that the shadow chancellor's decision showed that he was a 'strong,
courageous and confident man' who 'put the good of the party first'.
Some union leaders fear that if Mr Blair wins a landslide victory as an
uncompromising moderniser he may attempt to reduce the power of the unions
in the Labour party.
Others are confident that Mr Blair supports the party's commitment to full
employment and the introduction of a national minimum wage. They also
believe he would not wish to re-open the controversial issue of the role of
the unions in the party this side of the next general election.
Last night a spokesman for Mr Brown said that Mr Blair had agreed to back
the employment agenda outlined by Mr Brown in his recent speeches.
Union leaders on the centre-left are becoming reconciled to the prospect of
Mr Blair as leader - but they remain determined to uphold their authority in
the party and hold him to Labour's current economic policies.
However, they are also concerned at the findings of the opinion surveys that
suggest most political levy-payers in the unions are likely to back Mr Blair
and not Mr John Prescott, Labour's employment spokesman who is a favourite
among union activists.
