<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / Jamaica will help US in processing Haitians
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CANUTE JAMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KINGSTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Jamaica and the US will sign an agreement this week for the Caribbean island
to be the first country to help Washington in processing Haitians seeking
asylum in the US.
Haitian refugees intercepted at sea by US forces will be questioned on ships
anchored in Jamaican territorial waters.
Mr P J Patterson, Jamaican prime minister, told parliament last night that
the agreement will involve the stationing of 'one or two boats', and that he
expected the operation to last 'no longer than six months.'
There were reports last night that the US was considering the use of three
vessels - two cruise ships and a floating hospital.
The agreement concludes discussions between the two countries which started
a fortnight ago when President Bill Clinton wrote to Mr Patterson to ask for
Jamaican assistance in the new US policy of processing Haitian
asylum-seekers at sea or in a third country, rather than returning them to
Haiti without a hearing.
The prime minister did not say when the agreement will take effect and when
the processing will begin. Jamaica had agreed to its territorial waters
being used because of its concern for the humanitarian problems caused by
the present Haitian situation, and because of the Jamaican government's
support for the restoration of democratic government in Haiti, Mr Patterson
said. Haiti is one of Jamaica's closest neigbours.
The US-Jamaican negotiations gathered steam this week with visits to Jamaica
by Mr Strobe Talbott, US deputy secretary of state, and Mr William Gray,
President Clinton's special advisor on Haiti.
It seems the US had sought permission from the British government to use the
Turks and Caicos Islands, a British archipelago to the north of Haiti in the
Caribbean, as a station for processing Haitians. However, there was deemed
to be not enough room on and near those islands, according to Jamaican
officials.
The agreement by Jamaica and the US will not commit the island to admit any
Haitian refugees, and all costs of the operation will be met by Washington,
Mr Patterson said.
The US president's decision to have requests by Haitian refugees for asylum
processed at sea or in a third country followed criticism of the US
government's policy of intercepting Haitian boatpeople and returning them to
their homeland without hearing their claims for political asylum.
Human rights groups have consistently charged that some of the Haitians who
were returned by the US Coast Guard have been killed or otherwise abused by
the Haitian military, which has been running the country since it overthrew
and exiled President Jean-Bertrand Aristide two and a half years ago.
</TEXT>
