<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / Poland stays on reform course
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Poland is to press ahead with painful reforms of the welfare system, aimed
at cutting budget spending, as well as the consolidation and privatisation
of the banking system. The capital market is to be strengthened through the
development of investment and pension funds, according to a medium-term plan
prepared by Mr Grzegorz Kolodko, the new deputy premier and finance
minister.
The outlines of the plan were published yesterday as Poland started talks
with a team from the International Monetary Fund on a new one-year stand-by
agreement. The government plan, which runs until 1997, foresees an average
annual growth rate of 5 per cent. It forecasts the achievement of
single-figure inflation in 1997, compared with its present 25 per cent rate.
The government also wants to see a reduction in the spread between lending
and deposit rates.
The unemployment rate is forecast to fall from 16 per cent to 14 per cent,
while the budget deficit is to reach no more than 3 per cent of GDP in 1997,
from its present 4 per cent.
</TEXT>
