<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / Costs of Berlin move approved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The German government yesterday approved sharply scaled-down plans for
moving to the capital, Berlin, cutting back on housing ministries in new
buildings. In an effort to trim the costs, many ministries will be put into
old buildings which housed the former imperial, Nazi and communist
administrations.
However, the chancellory will be one of the few institutions to be given a
new site, close to the former Reichstag parliament building. The foreign
ministry, which had lobbied hard to have a new headquarters, will be given
only a new extension in the Mitte, the heart of old Berlin before the second
world war. The finance and economics ministers will move to the building
which now houses the Treuhand privatisation agency, but which was the
headquarters of the Luftwaffe. The construction minister, Mrs Irmgard
Schwaetzer, said the new plan will save the government around DM1bn,
reducing the total costs to around DM20bn.
