<HEADLINE>
FT  02 JUN 94 / Bond prices fall again in Europe on inflation fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
European government bond markets posted further declines yesterday amid
renewed fears of inflation. But the US Treasury market rebounded from a
morning sell-off triggered by evidence of growing price pressures in the
manufacturing sector.
In Europe, dealers reported selling mainly by institutional investors who
had been sitting on loss-making positions for months. This combined with
technically-driven selling in the futures markets to push prices in many
markets to new lows for the year.
Shares in London and Paris were dragged lower by the weaker bond prices,
while German stocks edged higher but finished well below their best. The
FT-SE 100 index closed down 38.6 at 2,931.9, its lowest finish since July.
French shares ended with sharp losses, with the CAC-40 closing 50.22 lower
at 1,972.18, below 2,000 for the first time since July.
US shares lost ground in the morning but recovered in tandem with US bond
prices. The Dow Jones Industrial Average, down as much as 25 points during
the day, finished up 2.46 at 3,760.83.
An unexpected jump in prices paid by US manufacturers in May, revealed in a
survey by the National Association of Purchasing Managers, set off the early
weakness in US bonds. The rally came amid further declines in commodity
prices and talks of unannounced bond purchases by the Federal Reserve. US
bond traders were awaiting tomorrow's May employment data. The Commerce
Department report is expected to provide further clues on US monetary
policy.
Higher-than-expected German industrial production data con-tributed to the
fall in European bonds. The UK gilts market was one of the worst performers,
plagued by fears that the economic recovery will fuel inflationary pressures
and lead to monetary tightening.
The June contract of the UK government bond future traded on Liffe, the
London futures and options exchange, broke through 100 and fell as low as 99
17/32 before closing around 99 25/32 , down 1 1/32 .
Despite a small reduction in the Bundesbank's securities repurchase rate, by
5 basis points to 5.15 per cent, sentiment remained negative on German
interest rate movements. The repo rate is used as a benchmark for interest
rates in German money markets. German government bonds were also sold
following remarks by Mr Guntram Palm, a member of the Bundesbank's
policy-making council, indicating that interest rate cuts in the near term
were unlikely.
German bonds did not suffer as much as other European bonds. The June Bund
futures contract on Liffe fell to around 92.30, down 0.54. Bond markets in
Scandinavia and southern Europe were hit by heavy foreign selling.
Industrial price increases revive fears of inflation, Page 8; Lex, Page 22;
Government bonds, Page 30; World stocks, Page 39; London stocks, Page 42
</TEXT>
