<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stock index futures came under renewed selling pressure, taking their cue
from international bond markets, writes Steve Thompson.
A steady opening at 2,941 by the June contract on the FT-SE 100 quickly gave
way as big sellers moved into the market. This followed a slide in German
bunds and UK gilts after news that the Bundesbank had withdrawn the bund
issue scheduled for this month.
With selling pressure building up during the mid-morning period, June fell
sharply to trade at a discount of 30 points to the cash market, reaching a
low point of 2,901 around lunchtime. This level triggered substantial bear
closing and a squeeze developed. June was subsequently driven up to a
closing level of 2,959, a discount of 14.5 points to the cash market, with
sentiment helped by a better than expected opening on Wall Street.
Dealers described the market as extremely nervous and driven by worries of
increasing inflation in the US and the UK. Turnover in the June Footsie
future reached a heavy 21,246 contracts.
Traded options were dominated by the FT-SE 100 and Euro-FT-SE contracts,
which together accounted for 26,019 trades out of a total turnover of 38,302
lots.
J. Sainsbury was the most heavily traded stock option.
</TEXT>
