<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Stocks mixed as data fail to
lift bonds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks were mixed yesterday as a batch of weaker than expected economic
data failed to lift bond prices, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 1.23 better at 3,758.37, while the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was down 0.83 at 456.50. Declines on the New York SE
outpaced advances by 1,193 to 950 after modest volume of 216m shares. The
American SE composite slipped 0.49 to 440.45 but the Nasdaq composite
improved 2.05 to 735.19.
After the extended holiday weekend, the trading week opened with a barrage
of economic news, which mostly pointed to a moderating economic trend.
The Conference Board, an industry trade group, said its May index of
consumer confidence slipped after advancing in the previous two months.
The Commerce Department announced that personal income in April was up 0.4
per cent, a little less than expected, while personal spending dipped 0.1
per cent, against expectations of no change. New home sales in April showed
a 6.8 per cent decline.
None of these indicators of slower growth - a favourable development for
fixed-rate investments - could generate any enthusiasm among bond traders.
The US Treasury market was showing moderate losses near the end of the day,
as the market watched commodity and gold prices rise and European bonds
extend their losses.
A report showing Chicago's purchasing managers paying higher prices last
month was another negative factor. The data may have provided a preview of
today's critical National Association of Purchasing Management survey.
There is also concern in the financial markets over May employment data, due
out on Friday. A strong reading on non-farm payrolls could trigger a big
sell-off in bonds. Stocks are sure to follow.
Blue chips were down 15 Dow points near the opening, as equity investors
pondered the weakness in bonds. But share prices later recovered to near
their opening levels as the session progressed.
American Express showed the best gain among the Dow components, up Dollars 1
5/8 at Dollars 27 5/8: the company completed the distribution of 98.2m
shares of Lehman Brothers (off Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 18), finishing the
spin-off of the investment banking firm. McDonald's added Dollars 1 1/8 at
Dollars 62 1/8 on the heels of announcing a two-for-one stock split and a
heftier dividend. Merck was up Dollars 1 at Dollars 62,
On the downside, Walt Disney shed Dollars 1 to Dollars 43 1/4 and Union
Carbide lost Dollars 1 to Dollars 27.
Blockbuster Entertainment, whose proposed takeover by Viacom has become
uncertain, was near the top of the NYSE's most active list. It rose Dollars
1 3/8 to Dollars 28 1/4 on volume of 3.2m shares after Robertson Stephens &amp;
Company lifted its rating on the issue. Two entertainment software companies
also announced a marketing pact with the video rental chain.
Bombay, a home-furnishing retailer, jumped Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 15 7/8
after posting a 23 per cent increase in May sales for stores opened at least
a year.
CBS suffered a further fall in the aftermath of last week's announcement
that several television stations were switching their affiliation to the Fox
network. The issue dropped Dollars 8 7/8 to Dollars 261.
Canada
Toronto also ended on a mixed note following moderate trading. The TSE 300
index gained 6.1 points at 4,326.8 but falls narrowly led rises by 409 to
401. Volume was 48.1m shares.
Eight of the 14 sub-indices were lower, led by transportation, off 1.6 per
cent. The gold group rose 1.6 per cent as the New York bullion price put on
USDollars 2.40 to USDollars 387.15 an ounce.
