<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / International Company News: Bank of Nova Scotia ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bank of Nova Scotia, Canada's third-biggest bank, had second-quarter net
profits of CDollars 187m (USDollars 135m) or 76 cents a share, excluding
special charges, up from CDollars 172m or 71 cents a year earlier.
Return on average assets was 0.66 per cent against 0.72 per cent, and on
equity 13.5 per cent against 14.2 per cent.
The bank took special after-tax charges of CDollars 305m relating to the
purchase of Montreal Trust and the write-down of goodwill for another
acquisition.
First-half earnings were CDollars 384m, up 14 per cent, but after the
charges were CDollars 79m, or 15 cents, against CDollars 337m, or CDollars
1.41, a year earlier. Total assets at April 30 were CDollars 127bn, up 27.5
per cent, largely due to the Montreal Trust acquisition and the impact of
the lower Canadian dollar.
Net interest income was little changed, but non-interest income rose 29 per
cent, due to strong brokerage and investment banking revenues. Non-interest
expenses rose 41.5 per cent with the addition of Montreal Trust's costs.
The total loan-loss provision for fiscal 1994 is CDollars 567m.
Non-performing loans were down to CDollars 2.08bn on April 30.
</TEXT>
