<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / International Company News: Record result for Italian
utility
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Enel, Italy's state-owned electricity utility, yesterday announced record
profits for 1993, in preparation for privatisation, possibly before the end
of this year.
The group, which is directly owned by the Italian treasury, reported a net
profit of L344bn (Dollars 216m), compared with L234bn in 1992, after
depreciation of L6,152bn against L6,129bn a year earlier.
The gross operating margin in the group's industrial operations increased by
3.7 per cent against the background of a 0.4 per cent increase in sales and
unchanged tariffs during 1993. The group said that its costs had been
reduced by 4.3 per cent in the year, or 8.6 per cent in real terms.
Investment in power stations during the year was 14 per cent lower than the
previous year at L8,749bn, but the group said this was due to the difficulty
of getting permission for new construction and the poor economic situation.
The group said that the results showed Enel was economically healthy,
efficient and with good growth prospects, elements which would lead to a
successful sell-off.
