Video stores this summer, writes Louise Kehoe in San Francisco.
The system has been jointly developed by NewLeaf Entertainment and Fairway
Technologies, both joint ventures between IBM and Blockbuster. It allows
video game software to be stored on computers installed in retail stores and
downloaded on-demand on to specially-designed reprogrammable video game
cartridges.
