<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / UK Company News: B&amp;J shareholders reject rescue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Gerald and Vera Weisfeld, the millionaire couple who founded the What
Everyone Wants chain, did not get what they wanted yesterday as shareholders
in discount retailer Brown &amp; Jackson rejected their rescue plan at an
extraordinary meeting in London.
The company could now face legal action arising from its decision to
recommend a second rescue package in preference to that of the Weisfelds.
It was clear from his statement that Mr Weisfeld, who had previously
refrained from commenting on the competing rescue offer from South African
group Pepkor, was angry.
The Weisfelds had offered to inject up to Pounds 28.4m, in return for a 43
per cent stake and two seats on the board. The board of B&amp;J had recommended
the Weisfeld's offer, until earlier this month when Pepkor offered an
injection of up to Pounds 56.3m for a 63 per cent stake.
The company said the Pepkor offer had been preferable as it meant B&amp;J would
get a Pounds 20m cash injection immediately. Mr Weisfeld said his efforts to
provide a similar immediate injection had been hampered by a lack of
financial information from the company.
Shareholders representing 58.6 per cent of the votes cast rejected the
Weisfeld's offer. An egm will be held on June 3 to vote on the Pepkor
proposals.
</TEXT>
