<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / Two Warburg directors paid Pounds 1m-plus: Late starter
shows rapid growth in off-balance sheet derivatives contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two directors of SG Warburg, the UK-based investment bank, received more
than Pounds 1m in salary and bonuses last year, as emoluments to the bank's
directors nearly doubled to Pounds 10.7m, it was disclosed yesterday.
Warburg revealed in its annual report for the year to March that one
director received Pounds 1.2m and another Pounds 1.5m. In each case, more
than Pounds 600,000 came under a long-term performance-related bonus scheme.
Sir David Scholey, chairman, received Pounds 758,000 compared with Pounds
411,000 in 1992-93. Some 11 Warburg directors were paid more than the top
amount of Pounds 510,000-Pounds 515,000 received by a director in the
previous year.
The bank also disclosed a rapid growth in its off-balance sheet financial
derivatives contracts. It held exchange rate, interest rate and equity
contracts with a notional value of Pounds 61.6bn at the year-end, compared
with Pounds 23.9bn.
However, the total replacement value of the contracts - the amount which it
would have to provide if the other parties to all its derivatives contracts
defaulted - grew only slightly to Pounds 597.4m, against Pounds 586m.
The figures, disclosed for the first time under the EC Bank Accounts
directive, showed rapid growth in equity derivatives contracts, an area
which it strengthened last year with the acquisition of the Chicago firm
KC-CO Investments.
Lord Cairns, Warburg's chief executive, said last week when the results were
released, that it had entered derivatives 'rather late in the day' and its
activities in the area were still 'relatively small'.
Mr Philip Gibbs, an investment banking analyst for BZW, said that the
figures did not indicate much about the shape of Warburg's derivatives
activities, but growth in derivatives was encouraging because it was a
profitable business.
Warburg also disclosed a fall in the proportion of pre-tax profits coming
from the UK: Pounds 196.1m, or 66 per cent, of the Pounds 297m total
compared with 83 per cent of Pounds 148.2m the previous year. But Warburg
added that more than 60 per cent of revenues came from outside the UK last
year.
The proportion of profits coming from the Asia Pacific rose to 13.9 per
cent, compared with 3.7 per cent.
Accounting issues, Page 26
</TEXT>
