<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / BT-MCI deal to get go-ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Telecommunications is set to gain the consent of US regulatory
authorities for its Dollars 5.3bn (Pounds 3.5bn) alliance with MCI, the
second largest US operator.
The US Department of Justice, and the Federal Communications Commission, the
US telecommunications regulator, may clear the BT deal as soon as this week,
following a year-long inquiry. 'All the lights are green,' said an industry
source.
Regulatory approval for the BT/MCI deal, signed last June, has taken far
longer than expected, leading to repeated postponements of the launch of a
joint venture between the two operators. The European Commission cleared the
alliance last September.
A Dollars 1bn joint venture company, geared to the international telecoms
needs of multinationals, will be launched soon, based in Washington. BT will
also be free to complete its Dollars 4.3bn purchase of 20 per cent of MCI.
The FCC's ruling will be tied to conditions, but they are not believed to be
onerous on BT.
Disputes between rival US/UK operators as to the openness of their
respective telecoms markets have dogged the approval process. AT&amp;T, which
competes fiercely with MCI in the US long-distance market and with BT
internationally, claimed the UK to be less favourable to new operators than
the US.
Consent for the BT/MCI deal does not finally resolve the issue. A separate
BT application to resell leased telecoms lines in the US is still pending,
as is an application by Cable &amp; Wireless, the UK's second largest telecoms
group, for a waiver allowing it to have stakes exceeding 25 per cent in US
cellular mobile operations.
AT&amp;T also has an application pending in the UK for full access to the UK
public network.
Regulatory authorities on both sides of the Atlantic have privately
expressed optimism that each will soon be able to pronounce the other
broadly equivalent in terms of openness.
That would permit the granting of consent to the outstanding applications,
and open the way to 'international simple resale' between the US and UK -
competition by leased-line operators offering services across the public
networks in both countries, which could significantly reduce transatlantic
telecoms prices.
Several large US telecoms operators are active in the UK's cable and
cellular mobile markets. Two of them - Nynex and US West - have supported
Cable &amp; Wireless's waiver application before the FCC.
</TEXT>
