<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / Independents fail to secure review of British Gas assets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Independent gas marketers have failed to persuade Ofgas, the gas industry
regulator, to order a root-and-branch revaluation of the assets of British
Gas's transportation and storage system.
The independents believe the current valuation of the assets is too high,
and have lobbied strongly for Ofgas to reappraise it in its forthcoming
consultation paper on transportation and storage charges.
British Gas will charge the independents for use of the transportation and
storage system, but its earnings from this will be limited by applying a
permitted maximum rate of return to the value of the assets.
If, as the marketers believe, the assets are valued too high, British Gas
will be able to justify higher charges.
That would limit the ability of the independents to offer cheaper prices to
customers once the phased opening of the domestic market begins in 1996.
Ofgas officials say there is no time to launch such an extensive exercise in
the run-up to competition. They will instead rely on the assumptions used in
1992, when they devised the present tariff formula, which is presently set
at retail price index minus 4 percentage points.
At that time, Ofgas commissioned an independent assessment, which valued
British Gas's transportation and storage assets at about Pounds 17bn, a
figure with which British Gas broadly agrees but which some independent
marketers say is 'hopelessly inflated' because the system has been built to
too high specifications.
The marketers have also questioned whether British Gas needs all the assets
it has placed in transportation and storage.
Ofgas plans a full review of the transportation and storage and tariff
formulas before 1997, when the present tariff formula ends. The
transportation and storage consultation paper will include details of the
formula that will govern the price British Gas can charge over the next
three years for its transportation and storage facilities, now known as
TransCo. The new system is expected to be working by October.
The Monopolies and Mergers Commission last year recommended a rate of return
for existing TransCo assets of 4 per cent-4.5 per cent, and 6.5 per cent-7.5
per cent for new assets. Ofgas officials say they would need a good reason
to do anything other than what the MMC recommended.
Some independent shippers have asked that a tariff of RPI -10 be set to
ensure that British Gas slashes what they consider to be an extravagant cost
base.
But Mr Cedric Brown, British Gas chief executive, recently warned that it
needs a 'return which will enable us to maintain a viable and safe pipeline
system and encourage new investment'.
</TEXT>
