<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / Labour plans curbs on hostile takeovers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour party plans due out tomorrow provide for a shake-up of corporate
governance and a clampdown on hostile takeovers. Pressures on companies to
pay high dividends to City institutions would be reduced.
Mr Robin Cook, Labour's trade and industry spokesman - and a potential
Labour leadership candidate - said yesterday he wanted to 'remove the
terror' that frightened company chairmen into paying big dividends.
'Companies often have to place dividends before investment because they fear
a fall in their share price will make them vulnerable to a takeover,' he
said.
In a paper called Winning for Britain, Mr Cook blames much of the decline in
investment performance on the fact that over the past 15 years the
proportion of net profits taken out of the business in dividends has
increased from half to three quarters. The government is also reviewing
whether companies are paying too much in dividends.
Mr Cook wants to reverse the burden of proof in takeovers on to the company
launching a hostile bid to show that it is in the public interest. At
present, a hostile takeover would be stopped only if it clearly transgressed
competition rules.
Mr Cook accepts that curbing the number of hostile takeovers - expected to
increase again after a lull during the recession - will not be sufficient to
ensure that companies invest more and improve performance.
He is proposing a package of measures designed 'to encourage committed
owners, promote collective contribution to the strength of the business
enterprise and raise the priority of long-term organic development of
businesses'.
They include tax changes to encourage long-term holding of shares; better
information for pension fund trustees; statutory reporting of long-term
indicators of corporate strength in annual reports; and a review of whether
to establish a minimum legal standard for the composition of company boards.
Although the plans are likely to upset business organisations, they are less
ambitious than Labour's previous policies and there is a strong stress on
changing corporate 'culture' and encouraging collaborative networking
between companies.
Big companies will only be encouraged rather than forced to introduce
Labour's favoured two-tier board option, with a supervisory board monitoring
an executive board.
Labour set to support lifting of BT ban, Page 12
Editorial comment, Page 23
</TEXT>
