<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / Bogus NVQ claims raise alarm: The questions posed about the
government's vocational qualifications system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A shiver has gone through the training industry after fresh allegations that
employees of a large provider of training made a further false claim for
funding on a government training programme.
The affair raises questions about whether it is possible for the new
national vocational qualifications system, on which the government is
pinning its hopes for on-the-job training, to be monitored properly. NVQs
are based on measuring an individual's competence on day-to-day tasks at
work. Full external assessment would be very expensive, so the system relies
on internal assessors giving accurate returns.
While the qualifications are verified by outside awarding bodies the
verifiers generally only see the paper records of achievements. There is no
formal requirement upon them to see whether the individual can actually
perform a task such as driving a tractor for a horticulture NVQ.
It can be tempting for unscrupulous assessors to exaggerate success by
asserting that a 'competency' has been achieved, as providers are
effectively paid by results. 'The system relies on the integrity and
professionalism of the assessor,' said Mrs Alison Wolf, reader in education
at the Institute of Education.
The events which have shaken the training industry centre on JHP Training, a
business and administration training provider, which is already under
investigation by the Department of Employment's internal audit service after
the disclosure last month that former employees obtained cash from Cumbria
Training and Enterprise Council for the attainment of NVQs based on bogus
claims.
The company admitted the original fraud, but said it responded openly and
promptly when it discovered that two or three former members of staff had
falsified documents.
A Commons motion tabled last week by Labour MPs Mr John Hutton and Mr Dale
Campbell-Savours named 'yet another victim' of the company in
Barrow-in-Furness which, it said, had claimed money for training he had not
attended. JHP has 'categorically' denied irregularity over this incident.
Mr Hugh Pitman, chairman and chief executive, said: 'The young man concerned
was being assessed for a qualification in the workplace while in a job. The
NVQ system was not properly explained to him. He thought that participating
in the scheme involved off-the-job training.'
JHP trains 10,000 people a year in 65 locations. 'To make sure everybody
obeys company policy is very difficult,' said Mr Pitman. 'We monitor our
work, as do Tecs and the Department of Employment. But there is still a
possibility of things going wrong.'
Several training providers say they are now ensuring that their internal
systems are secure. 'If you lose your good name in a system that relies on
integrity you are in trouble,' said Mrs Anne Weinstock, chief executive of
the Rathbone Society, a charity which trains 4,000 young people a year.
'There is no doubt that there is scope for sharp practice,' said Mr Ian
Christie of the Policy Studies Institute. 'But, it is very difficult to
quantify whether it is happening or not.'
Where the NVQs involve government-funded training it is the employer-led
Tecs in England and Wales which are responsible for arranging and paying for
the training.
Increasingly the government is paying Tecs for 'outputs': getting work or
qualifications for an unemployed individual rather than just paying him or
her to be on a course. Training providers which contract with Tecs risk
financial loss if outputs are not achieved.
Tecs are still refining quality-control systems. But they argue that their
new systems are a significant refinement on those of the employment
department when it ran publicly funded training programmes. Indeed, the
department's accounts were qualified three times by the National Audit
Office.
Tecs say that in the past a training provider would be paid when it informed
the department's local office that it had trained a certain number of
people. Now those Tecs which have invested fully in the new systems can
track a named individual through his or her complete training and monitor
progress.
The department says there is no evidence of widespread abuse of the system -
current abuses being investigated grossed up to about Pounds 15,000. It
rates most Tecs as of 'medium or low' risk in their quality control systems
for training. But the department, still scrutinising the JHP case, is
reviewing whether the NVQ system and safeguards are adequate.
A number of organisations, including the National Council for Vocational
Qualifications, which developed NVQs, say new checks may have to be
introduced, including substantial sampling of students by the external
verifiers. 'It takes time to build up consistent standards,' said the NCVQ.
Cumbria Tec, which made the payments to JHP, had for example three times
more people involved in financial appraisals than it inherited from the
employment department four years ago.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>JHP Training.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
