<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / Wales climbs wealth league
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Greater London remains the wealthiest region of the UK, but Wales, Scotland
and Northern Ireland are catching up, figures issued by the Central
Statistical Office showed yesterday.
In 1992, personal income per head in Greater London was Pounds 11,577, which
was 122 per cent of the average for the whole of the UK, while the
comparable figure in Wales and Northern Ireland was just Pounds 7,980 or
84.1 per cent of the average.
However, over the period from 1990 to 1992, incomes in Scotland, Wales and
Northern Ireland grew most strongly while growth in the south-east of
England and Greater London was below average.
Scotland climbed for the first time above the UK average in terms of
personal disposable income per head, which is calculated after deducting
factors such as taxes and the community charge. The county with the highest
level of income per head was Surrey, with an average of Pounds 11,225 in
1991. The wealthiest county outside England was Lothian, with an average of
Pounds 9,510.
The poorest county in terms of income per head was Mid Glamorgan, with an
average of Pounds 6,858. The poorest English county was Durham, with an
average of Pounds 7,312.
Economic Trends. HMSO. Pounds 13.25.
</TEXT>
