<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / Redwood denies grant claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Redwood, Welsh secretary, yesterday rejected allegations that Pounds
7m of government grants had been illegally channelled to marginal
constituencies in mid Wales.
In a BBC Wales television programme screened last night, it was claimed that
the money was disbursed via the Welsh Development Agency after the region
lost its assisted area status in 1982.
It was alleged that, under the 1975 act which set up the WDA, the agency had
no legal powers to do this.
Mr Jon Owen Jones, Labour MP for Cardiff Central, called on Mr Redwood to
resign. 'It's a clear case of the political masters deciding that the money
should follow their own perceived political advantage,' he said.
Mr Redwood accused the BBC of 'not doing its homework' and described the
allegations as 'scandalous'. He said: 'The legal advice I have is that the
powers are available under the WDA act.'
Parliament had been told in 1982 about the aid and it had not been
challenged. 'This is just a sign that we have an election coming up,' said
Mr Redwood. But he said he would call for a report from officials.
The Welsh Office said: 'The money has been used to finance business in mid
Wales, has created hundreds of jobs legitimately and has been audited. There
is no evidence at all that the scheme has been used for wrong purposes.'
In last night's programme, Mr Michael Henry, a former WDA director of
corporate services, said he had received legal advice that the grant aid was
outside the agency's powers, but had been told not to take it further.
Mr Henry was dismissed last autumn in the wake of criticisms of the agency
by the Commons public accounts committee, and is claiming unfair dismissal.
Mr Ron Davies, shadow Welsh secretary, said yesterday the government had
made a mistake in scrapping assisted area status for mid Wales.
'The whole incident highlights the incompetence and stupidity of government
policy and the way they have handed over an increasing range of public
services and taxpayers' money to unaccountable bodies,' he said.
Re-enter the dragon of controversy, Page 22
</TEXT>
