<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / Societies under probe by Treasury
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is considering ways of making building societies more
accountable to their members as part of the Treasury review of the 1986
legislation which governs societies.
But societies are set to retain some protection from predatory takeover
offers by banks or other organisations.
In a delay to the original schedule, the first stage of the review is now
expected to be announced to the Commons in the second half of this month.
Officials have submitted initial views, but ministers have yet to decide
what changes they wish to make.
The review, set up in January, will also have to take account of the outcome
of the legal challenge to the agreed Pounds 1.8bn Lloyds Bank offer for
Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Building Society. The two days of hearings ended
last week, but judgment has been reserved.
Despite the lobbying from banks such as Abbey National and TSB Group,
ministers see political disadvantages in exposing societies to hostile
takeover offers by other institutions.
There is a recognition at the Treasury, however, that corporate governance
arrangements which were adequate when societies were smaller organisations
now need changes. The largest societies each have more than 1m members.
Although many societies insist they are already accountable, measures to
improve accountability appear to be the price they will have to pay for the
greater freedoms they will enjoy as a result of the review.
Among suggestions to the Treasury is a requirement that, if a society's
board advises accepting an offer from a bank, then it should obtain two
independent valuations to ensure that members do not lose from the society
being undervalued.
The second stage of the review is likely to consider what specific changes
can be carried out through existing powers, through the new powers which
will be available from the de-regulation bill currently before parliament,
and what would require new legislation.
Some existing restrictions on societies - most notably the ceiling of 40 per
cent on the amount of funds they can raise on the wholesale market - look
certain to be relaxed.
Bank lending, Page 12
</TEXT>
