<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / European Elections: Edgy Tory walks along a thin tightrope
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Christopher Prout has a slightly edgy look as he sits each morning on
the platform at Conservative Central Office to be quizzed by the media about
next month's European elections. Friends of the MEP, who leads the Tory
group in the Strasbourg assembly, say his demeanour betrays nothing more
than his usual, pleasantly self-effacing disposition.
Political opponents judge that Sir Christopher, a committed European in a
party torn by internal divisions, is deeply embarrassed by the government's
negative campaigning.
Whatever the truth, he is walking the thinnest of tightropes. His strongly
pro-European instincts sit distinctly uneasily beside Mr John Major's
judgment that the Tories' best chance of avoiding annihilation on June 9 is
to pitch for the chauvinist vote.
Sir Christopher plays the game skilfully. A flick through his speeches
during 15 years in the European parliament leaves no doubt where he stands.
He does not advocate the monolithic superstate the government professes to
be battling against. But he is happy with words such as 'federal', with the
ambition of a single currency and the concept of more majority voting in the
Council of Ministers.
He insists relations between the 32-strong group of Tory MEPs and the
government have improved since the disastrous 1989 election when the MEPs
were driven to revolt by Baroness Thatcher's campaign against a 'diet of
Brussels'.
Not all colleagues are so sure. One Tory MEP was recently overheard
contrasting the government's attitude to its MEPs with its approach to the
IRA: ministers were at least prepared to talk to the terrorists.
Sir Christopher stresses that he regards the national veto so vigorously
defended by Mr Major as vital in the areas of foreign policy and taxation.
Transfer of authority on those issues to Brussels would 'erode the
sovereignty of the state and the sovereignty of Westminster'.
But, parting company with the likes of Mr Michael Portillo and others on the
Tory Euro-sceptic right, he added: 'It has always been my personal view that
it is possible to have a single currency without undermining national
sovereignty.'
Sir Christopher reinforces the point with a reference to the Victorian past,
when the currency was fixed to the gold standard: 'No-one imagined then that
the supply of money was not a fit matter to be left to the Bank (of
England).'
He is keen also to see the powers of the European parliament increased. Its
present authority to sack the European Commission in its entirety should be
extended to allow it to dismiss individual members of the executive, he
believes.
The assembly's powers of co-decision with the Council of Ministers should
apply in all areas where there is majority voting: 'It is important to have
a fuller democratic blocking mechanism.'
He takes issue with those in his party who believe that Britain's main task
over the next few years will be resisting the centralist juggernaut.
Although he does not fear economic and monetary union, he believes the
momentum has been lost. 'My view is that the time for a single currency has
probably come and gone.' Instead: 'The big problem that Europe is going to
face in the medium term is not centralisation. It is nationalism.'
He distinguishes between benign patriotism and malign nationalism: 'I am
quite fearful about the nationalism that feeds on enemies.'
Stressing that the EU must quickly enlarge eastwards, he warns that Germany
and Russia might otherwise divide up the former communist bloc countries of
central and eastern Europe into national spheres of interest. That last
happened in the late 1930s.
The way to stop history repeating itself is to build on the model provided
by the EU's precursor - the European Coal and Steel Community  - and to
begin now the process of drawing in the former communist bloc countries.
It all sounds sensible stuff. But sadly it is not the message Mr Major
thinks will persuade disgruntled Tory voters to turn out and support the
party on June 9. Better to tell them that the government will fight off the
bureaucrats of Brussels while the opposition parties run up the white flag.
For his part Sir Christopher has a reasonable chance of holding on to the
Herefordshire and Shropshire constituency against a threat from both the
Liberal Democrats and Labour. Many of his colleagues will not be so lucky.
</TEXT>
