<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / World Trade News: Europeans seek role in Japan aircraft
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
European aerospace companies yesterday called on Japan to include them in
its latest attempt to fulfil a long-frustrated ambition of creating a world
class Japanese civil aircraft industry.
A committee of the European Business Community, Europe's main business lobby
in Japan, voiced dismay at the inclusion of Boeing as the sole western
aerospace group in an important government-backed development project for a
short range passenger aircraft, code-named YSX. China is also taking part.
The 70-80 seat carrier, due to come into service at the turn of this decade,
is 'the essence' of Japanese civil aerospace policy, according to Mr
Toshifumi Hirai, director of the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry's aircraft and ordnance division. As such, it is of vital interest
to foreign suppliers.
Miti officials stressed that the inclusion of Boeing in the initial research
for the YSX did not mean European suppliers would be excluded.
However, the EBC's aeronautics and space committee was unconvinced and
warned that the exclusion of European suppliers would 'further contribute to
the imbalance between the US and Europe in Japanese aerospace
collaboration'. Japan was depriving itself of the 'longstanding experience
of European manufacturers in the regional market', it said.
ATR, the Franco-Italian regional airliner-making joint venture, and
Saab-Scania of Sweden are among the groups angling for a stake in the
project.
Until last year, Miti was hoping to develop a medium range 150-seater
aircraft, the YXX, with Boeing. But the ministry had to freeze the YXX after
Boeing went for the cheaper option of updating an existing aircraft series.
Japan was unable to continue alone, a frustrating reminder of its dependence
on US aerospace technology.
</TEXT>
