<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / Setback for Latvian coalition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Latvia's government coalition partners appear to have been trounced in
Sunday's local elections in preliminary results which suggest a mixture of
discontent with economic reforms and wariness about attempts to mend
relations with Russia. The pro-monetarist Latvian Way and the Latvian
Peasants Union coalition government, which wants better protection for
farmers from western competition, have together maintained a course of
effective but unpopular financial stabilisation policies. The government,
which has also been hit by accusations that five cabinet ministers used to
work for the Soviet KGB before the republic gained independence, last month
concluded an agreement with Russia to withdraw troops from Latvia by August
31. The poll results, which partially benefit more extreme nationalists, may
also affect the government's progress in pushing through long-postponed
legislation clarifying which non-Latvians (who comprise 48 per cent of the
population) qualify for citizenship.
</TEXT>
