<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / Two countries plan to set up joint agency for arms
procurement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
France and Germany yesterday signalled their intention to set up a joint
arms procurement agency and to develop a new large military transport
aircraft and observation satellite system to give their forces more
'strategic mobility', writes David Buchan. Ministers 'approved the
orientations' for the new bilateral arms agency designed to co-ordinate the
two countries' numerous programmes. But in deference to European partners,
the communique said the Franco-German agency would be open to other members
of the Western European Union and that the ultimate aim was a wider
procurement agency under the WEU. The project for a four-engine transport
with a 25 tonnes capacity has industrial backing from Deutsche Aerospace,
Aerospatiale, British Aerospace, Alenia of Italy and Casa of Spain, but so
far no government backing.
</TEXT>
