<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JUN 94 / PM signals readiness to opt out of EU integration
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major last night signalled that his government would be ready to opt
out of the next stage of European integration as he sketched out a
'multi-track, multi-speed' future for the European Union.
In a speech designed to unite the Conservative party by stressing his
determination not to cede further national sovereignty, the prime minister
flatly rejected the 'old centralised prescription'.
Instead he insisted that 'a new vision of Europe' was emerging in which 'the
functions of the Community should be carried out in different ways, often
involving different groups of states'.
Speaking at a European election rally in Ellesmere Port, he added: 'I have
never believed that Europe must invariably act as one on every issue. Trying
to make every country conform to every plan is a socialist way of thinking:
it not for us.'
The prime minister's comments marked out the growing difference of approach
between Britain and some of its EU partners over the evolution of EU
decision-making.
Earlier this week, Mr Alain Lamassoure, France's minister for Europe, hit
out at governments seeking to slow the pace of European integration and
called for more centralised decision making.
But Mr Major said yesterday: 'I don't happen to think that it threatens
Europe if member states are free to do some things in their own way and at
their own speed.'
Senior Conservative party officials insisted he was not suggesting Britain
would join the 'slow lane' of a two-speed Europe.
Mr Major also made it clear that he was not raising the possibility that
Britain - or any other EU state - could 'duck out' of commitments made in
the past.
But the speech was immediately seized on by opposition parties as an
admission by the government of its failure in Europe. Mr Jack Cunningham,
Labour's foreign affairs spokesman, said that in order to hold together the
Conservative party, the prime minister 'is apparently willing to offer
voluntary relegation to the second division in Europe'.
The idea of a multi-speed Europe has been floated several times in recent
weeks by Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, as a possible outcome of
the 1996 intergovernmental conference on the next stage of European
integration.
But last night marked the first time that Mr Major had taken up the theme of
so-called 'variable geometry'. He also used his second rally of the campaign
to warn that the opposition parties would allow Brussels to dictate
Britain's taxation and foreign policies.
Surrender of the national veto would threaten Britain's Pounds 3bn rebate
from Brussels and could also lead to higher taxes set by the EU and to a
loss of control over Britain's own foreign policy interests, Mr Major said.
Edgy Tory walks a thin tightrope, Page 10
</TEXT>
