<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / International Company News: German banks in talks over
Castle Energy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LINDEMANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The group of banks financing the DM3.4bn (Dollars 2bn) rescue package for
Metallgesellschaft yesterday discussed the future of Castle Energy
Corporation, the US oil refining group at the centre of the German company's
financial difficulties.
The future of Castle Energy in which the German company has a 40 per cent
stake became the subject of speculation following the announcement last week
by Metallgesellschaft that it will have to make provisions for new losses on
top of debt totalling DM9.2bn last March.
However, Deutsche Bank, which hosted the so-called steering committee, said
the meeting with representatives of the German group's board had been
relatively short.
It was held to inform the banks about a strategy unveiled by Mr Kajo
Neukirchen, the new chief executive drafted in after the group nearly went
bankrupt earlier this year, he said.
A source close to the talks said links between Castle and MG Corp, a
Metallgesellschaft subsidiary in New York, 'were so intensive' that a
decision to sell the stake was unthinkable.
MG Corp agreed to buy virtually all Castle's refinery output at prices above
the existing market, an unusual agreement which triggered the need for
further risk provisions.
