<DATE>940531
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Survey of German Banking and Finance (6): Old family houses
return / Examining the efforts to rebuild the banking system in the east
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nearly four years since German unification, the banking system and a range
of financial services are taking root in eastern Germany. But it is not only
the savings banks and Landesbanken, or state banks, which are being
re-established. The country's old family banking houses are returning, too.
But rebuilding a banking system has proved far from easy, says Mr Rudolf von
Sandersleben who represents the eastern states for Sal. Oppenheim, one of
Germany's oldest private banking houses which was founded in 1789.
Unlike western Germany after the second world war, which was still in a
position to lean on the mittelstand, the small and medium-sized enterprises
which formed the backbone to Germany's economic success over the past 40
years, no such sector existed in former communist eastern Germany. Moreover,
as Mr von Sandersleben points out, when Sal. Oppenheim opened its office in
Leipzig in 1990, the bank could not even lean on an entrepreneurial class.
'The entire memory of private enterprise had not been entirely wiped out,
largely because the last of the privately-run, very small businesses were
not banned until the early 1970s,' explained Mr von Sandersleben. 'But many
of these managers are now very old. Some of them have, however, tried again
to set up their businesses and revive that entrepreneurial spirit. But they
are few in number. We have to start from scratch.'
The absence of the mittelstand sector, therefore, poses a set of different
challenges for the private banking houses. Moreover, the absence of an
industrial base, which spawned west Germany's mittelstand, means that
private bankers have to look elsewhere for business or, more importantly,
take considerable risk to finance young entrepreneurs anxious to set up a
business in the eastern states.
Even in this context there are problems. 'These small businesses have no
capital,' said Mr von Sandersleben. 'They have no reserves, unlike the west
German mittelstand which have had 20 or 30 years to build up reserves which
can be used to invest, market, and make use of their capital.'
What, then, is the strategy the private banking houses have adopted in
eastern Germany? Sal. Oppenheim, for the moment, is 'going for the big fish'
 -those enterprises with a turnover of at least DM100m. These include the
utilities, for example, which are already largely dominated by west German
companies. Sal. Oppenheim is also more intent on finding ways to finance
their surplus liquidity than homing in on very small companies.
At the same time, the bank is playing a considerable role in consulting and
financial engineering. Yet the private bankers admit that many of the
companies in eastern Germany are not yet ready for such sophisticated
instruments of financing. 'What they still lack are the tools which are
vital for surviving: marketing expertise, risk capital, reserves and
management know-how,' said Mr von Sandersleben. 'Many are struggling to
survive'.
Yet, according to the Federal Association for Germany's banks, (BDB) under
which the country's private bankers are grouped, these are precisely the
kind of tools the banking sector in eastern Germany is now providing. Last
year's figures for these activities seem to confirm this. For example, the
credit flows from the private banking sector increased from DM23bn in 1990,
to more than DM96.9bn in 1993. Almost half that credit has been earmarked
for the housing sector. The Hypotheken banks, which specialise in this
sector, have already lent DM46bn, while the smaller banks have extended more
than DM11bn of credit.
Investment in businesses, ranging from the small crafts sector to property
and the infrastructure, has also increased sharply, rising from DM2.7bn in
1991 to DM4.3bn in 1993, and is set to increase to DM6.2bn by the end of
next year.
Yet curiously, the private banks have increasingly shied away from lending
to enterprises under the Treuhand privatisation agency. By the end of 1990,
the private banks had extended loans totalling DM18.3bn to the agency, and
only DM4.7bn to non-Treuhand companies. This ratio was understandable, given
that there were few private enterprises at that time, everything was in flux
and, in any case, credit facilities to the Treuhand carried few risks. They
were guaranteed by the government and margins were high.
Yet, by the end of 1993, more than DM48.9bn of credits had been extended to
non-Treuhand enterprises, and less than DM8bn to those enterprises still
under the agency. 'We wanted to have the freedom to do our own advising and
financing and locate potential customers ourselves,' said one banker.
As the private banks identified their niches throughout eastern Germany,
they also employed more people, crucial in a region which is facing
unemployment rates of more than 17 per cent. The number of jobs created by
the private banking sector rose from 18,000 in 1991 to over 21,000 in 1993.
But in creating jobs, the BDB believes is it also contributing to 'the
transfer of management know-how to the eastern states, which is a crucial
plank for restructuring the entire banking sector,' according to its
officials.
Bankhaus Lobbecke, which was founded in 1761 and which has opened branches
in Dresden and Magdeburg since unification, shares this philosophy. But
Konsul Gunter Follmer, the spokesman for the bank's partners, would go one
step further. 'Banking in eastern Germany is often pioneering work and it
still is. . .' Mr Follmer said. He added that Lobbecke wanted to support the
fledgling mittelstand sector. Indeed, by the end of last year, more than
DM1bn, or a third of its total credit volume, had been targeted on eastern
German clients.
There is hardly a banker who does not believe that eastern Germany needs a
mittelstand as much as the banks need these clients. 'The landscape will
change over the next 10 years,' said Mr von Sandersleben. 'But we will have
learned from our mistakes as well. And the existence of an overriding
bureaucracy is one of those mistakes. But that's another issue.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6081 Foreign Banking and Branches and Agencies.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
    MKTS  Market shares.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
