<DOCNO>FT942-6271</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EE4DFAEYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940531
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Survey of German Banking and Finance (7): Avoiding the
pitfalls / Profile of Salomon Brothers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Buried in the annual report of the Association of Foreign Banks in Germany
is a sentence which expresses foreign bankers' frustrations at doing
business in Germany.
'The universal banking system prevailing in Germany. . . knows how to
successfully prevent competitors from penetrating traditional business
relationships,' the report says, lamenting the fact that foreign banks'
share of the German banking market has stuck at a modest 5 per cent.
'Many foreign banks stub their toes in this market,' agrees Mr Nicholas
Coulson who joined the board of Salomon Brothers' German operations last
year.
Salomon is one which has managed to avoid the pitfalls and 'make intelligent
use of the opportunities' which present themselves in Germany, the former S.
G. Warburg executive says.
Salomon made DM40.3m net profits in 1992 and had a DM10.2bn balance sheet at
the end of that year. The figures for 1993 have not been released yet but Mr
Dan Lee, Arkansas-born managing director of Salomon's German operations,
says that they improved substantially.
In itself this is not surprising, given the excellent conditions prevailing
in the world capital markets last year, but there is no doubt that Salomon
has developed a strong franchise within Germany - the most recent figures
from the Association of Foreign Banks show that in 1992 Salomon was the most
profitable foreign investment bank in Germany, with the biggest balance
sheet.
If a year ago one had asked around the Frankfurt banking community why this
should be, rivals would have put it down to Mr Peter Coym and Mr Frank
Beelitz, the two men who opened up Salomon's German operation in 1986. But
they left last year to join Lehman Brothers where they are hoping to repeat
the success they enjoyed at Salomon.
Mr Lee argues that the personnel changes have had no disruptive impact on
Salomon's development - below board level, the senior management team has
remained extremely stable in the seven years that Salomon has been in
Germany, he says. The firm has done wll precisely because of the continuity
of client coverage in Germany, Mr Lee claims, combined with the ability to
deploy the resources of Salomon's worldwide network for the benefit of
German clients.
Another attraction has been a relatively cheap source of funds.
'Over the past seven years Germany has evolved to be one of Salomon's
cheaper sources of financing worldwide,' Mr Lee explains. 'This allows us to
run large trading positions here and to fund the rest of the group.'
The bank's profits, he says, come chiefly from trading in government
securities, equities and derivatives, and from capital market transactions
where the bank makes use of its international placing power.
In the Eurobond markets, it was joint lead-manager last year - with Deutsche
Bank - on the World Bank's D-Mark Global Bond issue, the first of its kind,
as well as on two smaller issues raising DM300m. In the domestic D-Mark bond
market it was lead manager on a DM750m issue for the state of
Baden-Wurttemberg.
This year, Salomon lead-managed the second-ever D-Mark Global Bond, a DM2bn
issue for the public sector L-Bank.
It was also co-lead manager, co-manager or underwriter in 11 Eurobond issues
and six domestic bond issues, following on from 100 such mandates last year.
The bank has about 125 people working in Germany: 40 on the trading floor,
55 in the back office and the rest providing corporate finance, mergers and
acquisitions, research and other services.
Salomon plans to expand at a pace consistent with the growth of new business
opportunities. Mr Lee stresses that there is no hurry to achieve any
targeted growth in personnel, recognising that finding the right people can
be difficult in Frankfurt, given the intense competition to employ native
Germans who have had experience of working in the Anglo-American financial
services sector.
</TEXT>
