<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Survey of the Computer Industry - Battle for the Desktop
(7): Stronger in niche markets / The competitive performance of
European-owned electronics companies is relatively poor. There are, however,
oases of excellence in an arid landscape - European suppliers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The European information technology industry is big, worth over Ecu120bn -
equal to Dollars 135.6bn or Pounds 94.4bn - in the EU countries alone, but
it is mostly foreign-owned. There are, however, some market niches where
European-owned companies seem able to hold their own with the rest of the
information technology world.
Supercomputing, remarkably enough, is one. Meiko, UK-owned with headquarters
in Bristol, England, and Waltham, Massachusetts, last year sold a Dollars
17.5m (Pounds 11.90m) machine to Lawrence Livermore Laboratory, a top US
research establishment more used to spending its money on American
supercomputers from Cray Research, the world leader.
Stern Computing Systems, based in Lyons, France, is meanwhile developing a
line of smaller, less powerful machines aimed at the technical computing
market rather than 'Grand Challenge' problems like modelling atmospheric
behaviour.
These, however, are oases of excellence in an arid landscape. European
computer hardware is dominated by US and Asian companies. The competitive
performance of European-owned electronics companies is poor, and shows
little sign of improvement. All the three indigenously-owned large
manufacturers - Siemens Nixdorf, Olivetti and Groupe Bull - are losing money
heavily.
The state-owned Bull is seeking private equity investment to strengthen its
balance sheet and persuade Brussels that further injections of capital from
the French government is essential for restructuring and not simply a
concealed subsidy.
The performance of indigenously owned PC companies including Vobis in
Germany, Tulip in Holland and Elonex in the UK is more hopeful, helped by
the fact that the professional microcomputer market grew at a healthy 8.8
per cent in units in 1993.
The fact remains that overall European electronics companies hold less than
30 per cent of their domestic markets for computers. By comparison, US and
Japanese companies control at least three-quarters of their computer
business in their home markets. According to Hubert Joly, Jurgen Kluge and
Lothar Stein, writing in the current issue of the McKinsey Quarterly, there
are three principles reasons for Europe's weakness in information
technology:
First, a concentration on high-end products supported by protected markets
and high prices.
Second, a lack of market-driven technological innovation and growth through
new products.
Third, a failure to adapt operations to changing competitive conditions.
They say 'the bad news here is that Europe cannot blame its poor showing on
the sluggish economy, industry cycles or higher factor costs. The problem
stems from missed opportunities to cope early on with the superior
approaches and faster pace of world-class competitors.'
Mr Franz Hetzenhauer, president and co-founder of Tulip Computers, believes
that the European Commission could and should do more to stimulate the
development of indigenously owned companies: 'It's very difficult to say we
have an industry,' he says. 'We are a small number of companies in a very
big market.'
He believes the EU should endorse a strategy for the industry recognising
that information technology will be one of the three largest global
industries by 2000 and should form one of the bases of Europe's prosperity.
He argues, for example, that European computer manufacturers should be
encouraged to collaborate with each other and with universities to eliminate
duplication of effort - 'everybody is building the same personal computer.
We are using our development funds the wrong way. It would be more efficient
to build everything but the final 20 per cent in common.'
The Esprit research programme, funded by the EU under its Framework research
initiative, was, he believes, too concerned with fundamental,
pre-competitive research.
A big issue is that the cost of manufacturing in Europe is high compared
with the US or Asia. Mr Hetzenhauer says that costs have to be stabilised,
tax rates cut and holidays curtailed. He also worries that illness levels
seem higher among European workers than their contemporaries in other
economies.
These social and macroeconomic issues apart, many manufacturers argue for
specific actions from the EU to cut the cost of manufacturing in Europe. Mr
Michael Spiro, finance director of Elonex, the fast-growing UK-based
microcomputer manufacturer, points to the import duties and anti-dumping
duties added to the cost of certain types of memory chip which, he reckons,
can add up to Dollars 50 to the price of a European-made machine.
The fact remains that indigenously-owned and foreign companies - with a few
exceptions including Compaq, the personal computer manufacturer - have found
the European market heavy going over the past few years. IBM and Digital
Equipment are among the companies which have blamed slow going in Europe for
poor results.
ICL, in which Fujitsu of Japan has a majority stake and which is the most
successful of the European-based large computer companies, has seen its
profitability fall steadily over the past three years.
This year pretax profits were a mere Pounds 23.4m and the company has
strengthened its balance sheet, raising a total of Pounds 100m from its
parent through a rights issue.
It is in a enviable position, however, compared with its European-owned
rivals. Groupe Bull's predicament is probably the most serious but Siemens
Nixdorf is still losing money and sales. Both sales and orders were down six
per cent at the half-way stage this year. In the past two years cumulative
losses have amounted to almost DM1bn.
Later this year, Mr Hans-Dieter Wiedig, head of Siemen's computer business
for the past 10 years, will hand over to Mr Gerhard Schulmeyer, formerly of
Motorola and Asea Brown Boveri, whose principal challenge will be to bring
the ailing company to break-even point by 1996.
Olivetti of Italy cut its losses in 1993 to L465bn (Dollars 283.53m)
compared with L650bn (Dollars 396.34m) the year before and increased its
sales for the first time since 1990. On the other hand, it failed to break
even at the operational level. The group has been boosted, however, by the
award of a licence to run Italy's second mobile phone network. Olivetti led
a consortium including Bell Atlantic, Pactel and Mannesman. It intends to
use the licence as the basis of a new network to serve mobile phone and
computer users.
Europe's chief hopes of a resurgence in information technology lie in new
technologies and combinations of technologies where leadership has yet to be
established.
Mobile communications and multimedia are two such areas. But European
companies will have to move faster than in the past if they are not to
repeats their past failures.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>XGZ  Europe.
</CN>
