<DATE>940531
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Survey of the Computer Industry - Battle for the Desktop
(8): A serious challenge from the US / Japan's computer companies become
more vulnerable to aggressive outside forces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The city of Mino, to the north of Osaka, may seem an unlikely site for a
progressive policy on technology. But the educational council in Mino broke
with widespread practice in Japan and chose Apple's Macintosh personal
computers for its 13 primary and seven junior high schools.
Japan's leading computer makers are being confronted with a serious
challenge from US companies like Apple to their own dominance in the home
market where they once ruled supreme.
Last year, Apple Computer won a 13.9 per cent share of Japan's personal
computer market, overtaking Fujitsu as the second largest PC vendor in Japan
after NEC, according to Dataquest, industry analysts.
US computer makers as a whole increased their share of the Japanese market
in 1993 to 24 per cent, up from 15 per cent in 1992, Dataquest notes. At the
same time, many Japanese computer makers themselves have started to market
IBM-compatible machines, completely reversing their previous strategy of
selling only their own proprietary systems in Japan.
Last October, Fujitsu, which had previously sold only PCs based on its own
architecture in the home market, began selling IBM-compatible computers.
Earlier this year, Seiko Epson, which had long stuck faithfully to NEC's
standard, also began marketing IBM-compatible machines in Japan for the
first time.
Apple's success in Japan and the growing trend among Japanese computer
makers to come out with IBM-compatible machines, point to a fundamental
change in the Japanese PC market that is forcing the country's computer
makers to confront difficult strategic decisions.
The hitherto protected Japanese market, which allowed Japanese companies to
set the standards and price levels, is becoming more vulnerable to outside
forces as a result of the aggressive entry into the market of US
manufacturers.
To be sure, NEC, the undisputed market leader, was able to maintain a market
share of just under 53 per cent last year despite fierce price pressures.
However, the presence of US makers in Japan has meant that Japanese
companies, including NEC, can no longer set the standards of price and
performance in their own market but must meet the more demanding standards
of the US, where competition has been more cut-throat than in Japan.
The consequence is that Japanese computer makers, which have not been
particularly competitive except in certain areas such as notebooks, have had
their weaknesses exposed in their own home market.
One such weakness has been in terms of cost. Competition from US companies
such as IBM, Compaq and Dell, which launched low-price models into the
Japanese market, has led to the collapse of the high prices which Japanese
computer makers enjoyed at home and has forced Japanese companies to tackle
their high cost structures.
Due to increased competition from US makers, and as familiarity among
Japanese consumers with computers has increased, PCs have increasingly come
to be regarded as commodity items and Japanese consumers have become much
more sensitive to the prices of PCs.
At the same time, Japanese companies have been struggling to continue to
come up with higher value-added products which can compensate for the
falling profitability of mass-volume PCs.
Steps are being taken on both fronts. In order to raise
cost-competitiveness, Japanese computer makers are shifting a greater
proportion of their manufacturing outside of Japan, where the yen's rise and
high labour costs have made manufacturing a relatively expensive activity,
and procuring more parts from low cost overseas sources.
NEC, for example, has launched an aggressive cost-cutting programme and has
introduced models since the beginning of last year with a price-performance
ratio of one-third to half the price-performance ratios of previous models.
The company plans to reduce costs by more than half over the next few years.
As part of its cost-cutting programme, it has this year started importing
motherboards from Taiwan for some of its PCs - a significant move since the
costs of motherboards accounts for a big proportion of the total cost of the
PC.
Companies with less of a presence in the PC market are resorting to OEM
arrangements to procure PCs at lower costs than they would be able to
manufacture them. Hitachi, for example, is buying IBM's PS/V series which it
will sell in Japan under its own brand while Sharp will buy IBM-compatible
machines from Taiwanese and Korean makers to sell under its own brand name
both overseas and in the home market.
But while such cost-cutting measures will have a beneficial effect on their
bottom line, Japanese computer makers also realise that they need to move
aggressively into more value-added products in order to boost profitability.
Here, some of the leading companies such as Toshiba and NEC, have an
advantage in their liquid crystal display operations which have provided
them with a leap over competitors in the notebook market.
Last year, NEC agreed to provide NCR, the US company, with notebook
computers under an OEM deal. NEC is increasing its investment in thin-film
transistor liquid crystal displays which provide the high resolution screens
that have made Japanese notebooks so popular. Other Japanese companies
including Fujitsu and Toshiba are also boosting investment in TFT-LCDs.
Their early investments in LCD are already paying off handsomely as notebook
PCs made by Japanese manufacturers have been highly popular in the buoyant
US market.
Japanese computer makers are also making further leaps into multimedia with
the introduction of PCs capable of displaying still photos, video and CD
sound.
However, as the multimedia industry develops, pulling in more elements of
the audio-visual and broadcasting industries into the world of the computer,
Japan's computer industry faces increasing competition not only from fellow
computer makers in the US, but from Japanese consumer electronics makers as
well.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>JPZ  Japan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P357  Computer and Office Equipment.
    P737  Computer and Data Processing Services.
    P3571 Electronic Computers.
</IN>
<XX>
