<PROFILE>_AN-EE4DFAEUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940531
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Survey of German Banking and Finance (4): An embarrassment
of riches - Developments in the banking sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Hilmar Kopper, the forthright chief executive of Deutsche Bank, is
renowned for his plain speaking.
Sometimes, though, he takes this a little too far - as when he dismissed as
'peanuts' the DM50m owed by the collapsed Jurgen Schneider property group to
trade creditors.
The off-the-cuff remark, in the middle of a long press conference on the
bank's role in Germany's biggest property bankruptcy since the second world
war, prompted outrage in the tabloid press and introduced another English
word into everyday use in Germany.
The bank was lead creditor to Mr Jurgen Schneider, the property entrepreneur
who disappeared after writing a letter to a Deutsche Bank board member in
early April.
At the press conference more than two weeks later the bank disclosed that it
stopped lending to Schneider in 1992 and had started to intensify checks
into Schneider's creditworthiness in February this year. But the bank was
satisfied with his answers to their queries and with his payments record and
had no suspicion that Mr Schneider was planning to abscond.
The 'peanuts' observation - for which Mr Kopper later apologised - served to
stir up the hostility of the general public to the big banks, so much so
that polls showed a majority blaming the bank for the collapse of Schneider
with debts of more than DM5bn - not Mr Schneider himself who has disappeared
with several hundred million D-Marks of funds owed to craftsmen and building
suppliers as well as banks.
That hostility has found expression in the success of a second best-selling
book from Mr Gunter Ogger, a business author who has an uncanny knack of
identifying popular issues.
His first book - Nieten in Madelstreifen (Nitwits in Pinstripes) - condemned
Germany's managerial and banking elite for complacency and cosy boardroom
connections.
Before too long, the near-collapse of Metallgesellschaft, the large metals,
mining and industrial group rescued in January - in which Deutsche Bank is a
big shareholder - duly bore out his scathing criticisms.
His second book is called Das Kartell der Kassierer (The Cartel of the
Rip-off Merchants). It condemns Germany's bankers for stripping Germany's
honest burghers of their hard-earned cash.
In vain can heavyweight bankers such as Mr Kopper or Mr Martin Kohlhaussen,
Commerzbank's chief executive, attempt to stem the tide of public opinion by
arguing that German banks preserve jobs by rescuing German companies during
recession - and that the solidity and profitability of the banking system in
general is good for Germany.
The strength of the German banks was illustrated in last year's results from
Deutsche: group operating profits rose by 16 per cent to DM5.3bn.
This was after making provisions for bad and doubtful debts. At Deutsche,
provisions were increased 72 per cent to a massive DM3.3bn last year.
It is in this context that Mr Kopper's 'peanuts' remark must be understood:
the DM50m owed to Schneider's trade creditors is, indeed, immaterial in the
context of the Deutsche Bank's own DM560bn balance sheet and its luxuriantly
healthy profit-and-loss account. The bank's provisioning is substantial
enough to swallow up the bank's unsecured exposure to the Schneider empire
of DM500m, and more besides.
Mr Kopper's public relations gaffe - and that of the bank in being slow to
recognise the wider implications of the debacle from the moment that it was
clear that Mr Schneider had left the country - was in failing to make a
clear distinction between the implications for the bank, and the quite
separate question of the impact on trade suppliers.
That failure has left the bank's more junior employees out in the branch
network facing anger and incomprehension from creditors harassed over much
smaller amounts of money than the DM50m which counts as peanuts.
'But I can assure you that I and my colleagues know the value of DM50m,' Mr
Kopper told disgruntled shareholders at the bank's annual meeting earlier
this month.
Whether the damage to the bank will be lasting, remains to be seen. Three
separate investigations - one by the BAK federal banking authority and two
internal ones - are under way and it is not impossible that heads will roll
as a result.
But despite a sharp fall in the share price in the immediate aftermath of
the affair, most analysts continue to see Deutsche Bank shares as an
attractive investment opportunity and the institution's formidable earnings
power undented by embarrassment over the Schneider affair.
The same is true for Germany's banking sector as a whole. Last year, one
after another reported record profits despite large increases in provisions
for bad and doubtful debts. At Dresdner Bank, profits were up by 24 per cent
to DM2.04bn; at Commerzbank, by 24 per cent to DM1.13bn; Bayerische
Vereinsbank, by 32 per cent to DM1.16bn and Hypo-Bank by 33 per cent to
DM1.04bn.
These figures reflect an extremely favourable constellation of circumstances
 -falling interest rates, booming financial markets, strong demand for
credit - which meant they could defy the deep recession in their home
market.
As bank chief executives acknowledged at this month's round of shareholder
meetings, these circumstances no longer apply - the bund market has, for
example, been in the doldrums throughout much of the early part of the
current year.
Although bank lending, at the core of mainstream banking business, continues
to rise at a double-digit rate and provisions are on the way down, bankers
predict that profits this year may be down from last year's record levels.
Mr Kopper said that group operating profits after provisions were down at
the Deutsche Bank by more than 10 per cent in the first four months of the
current year.
By contrast, Mr Jurgen Sarrazin, chief executive of the Dresdner Bank, said
that profits rose at a pleasing rate over that period, but he warned about
extrapolating the increase for the year as a whole.
As the German economy starts to pull out of recession, it may be that the
worst for the German banks is already over - and the worst constituted the
best year in their history.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6081 Foreign Banking and Branches and Agencies.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MKTS  Market shares.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT942-6276</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EE4DFAETFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940531
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Survey of German Banking and Finance (5): Highly innovative
issue - Dresdner Bank has transformed its image
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Dresdner Bank, Germany's second-largest German bank, is known at home for
being big, profitable and profoundly conservative. In north America, the
bank is not well known at all, concedes Mr Hansgeorg Hofmann, one of the two
board members at the bank in charge of investment banking.
At least, Mr Hofmann contends, the bank was not well known in the north
American financial community until April-May this year when it conducted a
capital-raising transaction which stood the bank's reputation for stodgy
conservatism on its head.
It became the first Germany company or financial institution to launch a
global issue of new shares.
The highly innovative issue was conducted against a difficult market
background. As shares in German banks tumbled amid the fall-out from the
collapse of the Jurgen Schneider property group, and north American capital
markets reeled from interest rate jitters, Dresdner Bank successfully placed
DM1.16bn of fresh equity with international investors.
To support the bank's cash-raising exercise, four board members left their
comfortable fastness in the centre of Frankfurt's banking district, and took
to the road. Together with a team of senior executives, they undertook the
undignifying task of going on a roadshow, conducting a total of 60
presentations to institutional investors in Europe, the US and Asia.
While this sort of thing is bread and butter work for Anglo-American
executives, it is still a new experience for senior German businessmen to
undergo the often humiliating experience of being grilled by pimply
financial analysts who may not have heard of the Dresdner Bank.
'This was pioneering work,' reflected Mr Hofmann. 'In the US we have never
visited institutions or made information available before. We felt that the
response was incredibly positive.'
The new shares, representing 7 per cent of the bank's equity capital, were
placed without pre-emptive rights for existing shareholders, although big
shareholders in the bank such as the Allianz insurance group (with a 22.31
per cent stake) did subscribe to the issue.
According to Mr Hofmann, who joined Dresdner in October 1989 after 20 years
in senior positions with US investment banks, the bank has benefited in a
number of concrete ways from the issue:
It managed to raise its profile with international investors, especially in
the US.
At 35 per cent, the percentage of shares owned by foreign investors is far
lower than at rival German financial institutions.
In the US, the bank's shares have traditionally been less popular with
investors than those of smaller German banks such as Commerzbank and
Bayerische Vereinsbank.
It has opened up a source of capital which may reduce the bank's financing
costs over the long-term - especially if demand from the international
investment community leads to a higher rating for Dresdner Bank shares.
The process of putting the issue together within a necessarily short
time-frame forced the bank to act in an entrepreneurial way.
Mr Hofmann says that traditional chains of management command and lengthy
decision-making processes were bypassed in order to get the deal done - a
healthy injection of Anglo-Saxon-style frenzy into the bureaucratic culture
of a traditional German bank.
The successful completion of the issue will have a powerful marketing
effect, giving Dresdner the chance to win lucrative global equity placing
mandates in the future (particularly in conjunction with the forthcoming
privatisations of Deutsche Telekom and Lufthansa).
Dresdner was joint global co-ordinator on the issue with Merrill Lynch - but
Mr Hofmann believes the financial technology associated with the issue is
not proprietory to the US investment banking community.
The bank was able take the offensive on the issue of German accounting.
Fund managers were especially impressed by the arguments deployed by Mr
Andreas Bezold, a former partner in Deloitte &amp; Touche who now heads up
Dresdner's finance deparment.
He denounced US accounting on issues such as marking securities to market
and the disclosure of derivatives risks, providing rare ideological support
for German accounting practices often, Bezold complains, condemned
unthinkingly by the Anglo-American investment community.
The US segment of the issue was placed with institutional investors under
Rule 144A of the US Securities Act. This mechanism allowed the bank to avoid
making the accounting disclosures required when a company seeks a full
listing for its shares on the New York Stock Exchange.
Dresdner was able to follow this route within narrow time constraints
because shareholders in the bank had some years ago given the bank formal
permission to issue up to 10 per cent of new shares without pre-emptive
rights. This was in the context of the planned share exchange with Banque
Nationale de Paris which has in the meantime become more modest in scope.
Mr Hofmann believes that the Rule 144A placing undertaken by the bank may
prove to be popular with German institutions in preference to obtaining a
full listing.
The German government is intending to introduce legislation allowing
companies to place up to 10 per cent of their shares without offering
pre-emptive rights for existing shareholders.
This move could encourage more German companies to tap the US financial
markets, the biggest source of capital in the world, following the Dresdner
model.
To date, Daimler-Benz, Germany's biggest industrial company, is the only
German group to have sought and obtained a full listing in the US. It came
to the US market last autumn - without an issue of new shares - in a move
which provoked outrage among fellow German companies indignant at the idea
of complying with US accounting requirements.
The total issue of new Dresdner shares was comfortably oversubscribed,
although Mr Hofmann admits that hopes of placing 770,000 American Depository
Receipts in the US were overly-optimistic. But in a week when 24 out of 39
equity issues planned for the US were postponed or cancelled, Mr Hofmann
declares himself delighted with the level of demand for the new Dresdner
shares from north American investors. The follow-up demand from US
institutions who did not originally take up shares has also been high, he
says.
</TEXT>
