<PROFILE>_AN-EE4DFAERFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940531
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Survey of the Computer Industry - Battle for the Desktop
(5): Unfashionable giants / Mainframes, for 30 years regarded as the central
focus of the data processing firmament, are being re-cast as high powered
network servers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mainframe computers, large, expensive and energy-hungry are deeply
unfashionable. They are, nevertheless, for a broad range of data processing
tasks, indispensable.
This is the mainframe manufacturers' chief dilemma. Each the suppliers in
this sector - and there is only a handful left - has important customers:
large enterprises, public utilities and the like, for whom mainframes are
essential. Only a mainframe can provide the memory, the raw computing power
and ability to support several thousand users and a multiplicity of tasks.
But the number of such users is unlikely to grow much. Indeed, over the next
decade or so, they will probably contract and with them the aggregate
revenues manufacturers derive from mainframe sales. Overall revenues for
Groupe Bull's UK subsidiary grew 35 per cent last year for example;
mainframe revenues were essentially flat.
All these customers have, however, to be supported. First, because
mainframes remain a powerful source of revenue. Mr Louis Gerstner, IBM's
chairman, might argue that the company 'no longer makes a lot of money on
mainframe computers,' but gross margins on large systems, while much reduced
from earlier years, are still appreciable. By comparison, a number of
manufacturers - Groupe Bull is one - have been losing money on their
personal computer operations.
Second, because it is important to keep faith with customers if they are not
to turn to other suppliers for their data processing equipment. All have
critical 'legacy' systems on which their business turns and which would
prove both inconvenient and expensive to rewrite.
Third, because the leopard is changing its spots: mainframes, for 30 years
regarded as the central focus of the data processing firmament, are being
re-cast as high powered network servers, designed to co-operate with other
computers instead of taking charge of the operation.
Mr Philip Crawford, managing director of Bull (UK) says: 'If we can continue
to drive down the cost of ownership while improving quality and
maintainability, there is no reason for users to rush to get off mainframes.
The only proper reason for downsizing is in pursuit of a business strategy,
not fashion.'
Many industry experts believe the move to client-server systems has been
driven more by fashion than by real user need, and that the true cost, per
workstation, of a client-server system is often under-estimated. They
believe that within a few years there could be a backlash against
client-server and Unix based systems which will see mainframes reinstated as
the centre of the data processing hierarchy.
The continued development, however, of mainframe technology is expensive.
Manufacturers are having to trade off investment in mainframes against
funding faster growing parts of the industry. And at the same time, the
price of mainframes is falling fast - at a rate of about 33 per cent last
year - both because the basic technology is becoming cheaper and because
manufacturers have to price their hardware in competition with apparently
cheaper industry-standard systems.
Mr Gerstner at IBM in a striking reversal of past policy has already made it
clear that the mainframe division no longer has first claim on the company's
research and development funds.
For some companies, mainframe ventures have proved a disaster. Digital
Equipment, once the leader in minicomputers, moved into mainframes with its
9000 series. Sales, however, were a fraction of expectations.
A number of alliances have been struck between companies to share costs and
technologies. Earlier this year Amdahl, a US manufacturer of computers that
are plug-compatible with IBM's announced an alliance with Fujitsu of Japan
which holds a minority stake in the US company. It calls for the two
companies to develop jointly the next generation of mainframes based on a
semiconductor technology called CMOS. The agreement is expected to reduce
research and development costs significantly for Amdahl.
ICL in the UK has already benefitted greatly from its technology alliance
with Fujitsu which has given it access to the Japanese company's
semiconductor and component technology at an early stage.
IBM earlier this year agreed to provide Hitachi of Japan - a bitter rival -
with the microprocessors at the heart of its newest systems. These are CMOS
chips that do not need the elaborate liquid cooling systems necessary with
earlier systems.
Earlier this month, NEC, the Japanese manufacturer which supplies Groupe
Bull with mainframe computers said the two companies are discussing
collaboration on the next generation of both mainframe and midrange
computers with the object of reducing the research and development burden
for both companies.
The implementation of CMOS chips in the circuitry of the latest mainframe
computers is significant. CMOS is widely used in personal computers where
its advantages lie in low power consumption and heat dissipation.
Increasingly, mainframe technology is being driven by personal computer
technology.
NCR, the US computer manufacturer taken over two years ago by AT&amp;T, led the
way in 1990 announcing that its entire range would be based on
microprocessors from Intel, the world's leading semiconductor company.
Over the next few years, a number of microprocessors and and processing
architectures are likely to jostle for position as the base technology for
large computer systems. They include Intel's 80/x86 range, IBM and Apple's
PowerPC, Hewlett Packard's PA Risc, and Digital Equipment's Alpha.
The trick will be to develop sound and reliable systems running many of
these chips in parallel. IBM, for example, is taking another crack at the
supercomputer market with a machine announced last month, the SP2, which is
claimed to offer up to 136 billions of floating point operations a second.
It is based on IBM's reduced instruction set computing (risc) chips, first
seen in the RS6000 workstation, running in parallel.
The launch of the SP2 is a big cultural change for IBM. One of its senior
executives once dismissed the significance of client-server computing with
the jibe that if you network together a thousand pocket calculators, it does
not make a mainframe. These days, given a little poetic licence, it does.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
