<PROFILE>_AN-EE4DFAEQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940531
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Survey of the Computer Industry - Battle for the Desktop
(6): New winners emerging / Delays in adjusting to shifts in computer usage
have proved costly for some of the largest system suppliers - US market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The financial problems of International Business Machines and Digital
Equipment have cast a pall over the US computer industry. Yet while these
two companies are struggling, the market is growing and some of their
competitors' sales are booming.
In particular, Hewlett-Packard has emerged as a new industry leader,
overtaking Digital to become second only to IBM among US companies in
computer revenues, while Compaq Computer goes from strength to strength in
the personal computers sector.
One of the most important factors that is sorting out winners and loosers in
the US computer market is the extent to which companies have adjusted to the
'new computing model,' based on networks of desktop computers, called
clients, linked to 'servers,' a term that covers the broad range of
computers that can be used to provide services on a computer network.
For IBM , with its roots firmly planted in centralised mainframe computing,
this
adjustment is proving difficultand painful - 'the failure to capitalise on
this sea-change in our industry (from centralised 'host' mainframe computer
systems to distributed networks) is the single most important mistake IBM
has made in the last decade,' Mr Lou Gerstner, IBM chairman and chief
executive, said recently.
Announcing plans to recast IBM's entire product line, he said that the
company must 'take all we know about powerful host-based systems and create
new products for the open, distributed world. We should have done it a
decade ago.'
Similarly, Digital Equipment was slow to react to changes in the computer
market, in particular the trend toward 'open systems' standards that make it
easier to link computers from different manufacturers into heterogeneous
client-server networks.
Although Digital was an early leader in distributed computing, its
traditional products were based on proprietary technology. Until the
appointment of Robert Palmer, who replaced company founder Kenneth Olsen as
president and chief executive in October 1992, Digital did not
wholeheartedly adopt the concept of open systems.
'We have finally established credibility in the UNIX (open systems)
marketplace after years of struggle and confusion,' said Mr Palmer said in a
recent address to employees.
These delays at IBM and Digital have proved very costly. Both companies have
recorded heavy losses over the past two years and although IBM has recorded
a small net profit in each of the past two quarters, Digital remains mired
in losses.
In contrast, Hewlett-Packard is reaping the rewards of an early shift to
open systems software and client-server computing. HP 'anticipated well
(the) necessary changes in technology,' says John Jones of Salomon Brothers,
the US broking house.
HP was in the forefront of the shift from proprietary computers to 'open
systems' based on industry standards. The company was the first to implement
Reduced Instruction Set Computing (Risc) technology in mid-range and
mainframe computer systems, providing high performance at lower costs.
HP has also been faster to come to terms with an industry-wide decline in
gross profit margins as computer prices fall. Over the past five years, it
has cut operating expenses from more than 40 per cent of revenues in 1988 to
28 per cent in the first fiscal quarter of 1994 (which ended on January 31).
For fiscal 1993, HP's net revenue rose 24 percent to Dollars 20.3bn,
compared with Dollars 16.4bn in fiscal 1992. Net earnings for the year were
Dollars 1.2bn, an increase of 21 per cent. Yet it would be a mistake to
dismiss HP's biggest competitors as 'has beens.' The remarkable turnaround
staged by Unisys is evidence that large, stumbing computer companies can
make a comeback. After three years of heavy losses, write-offs and layoffs,
Unisys has put its troubles behind it.
The turnaround began at the end of 1991, when Unisys recorded a modest
fourth quarter profit. The company has not looked back since.
Over the past two years Unisys' profits have doubled, to Dollars 565.4m in
1993. Net debts have been reduced from a peak of almost Dollars 4bn to
Dollars 1.1bn at the end of 1993.
'The turnaround is real . . . no management in the computer business has
executed better over the past two years . . .' commented Curt Rohrman of
First Boston in a recent report on the company.
Revenues, however, are still declining. For 1993, the company reported sales
of Dollars 7.7bn, down 23 percent from a 1990 peak of Dollars 10.1bn.
Currently only about 10 to 15 per cent of Unisys' sales are to new
customers. In a bid to boost flagging sales of mainframe computers, Unisys
has moved ahead of competitors in a transition to more cost efficient
semiconductor chips which will be manufactured for Unisys by its long-time
rival IBM.
Unlike traditional mainframes, Unisys' new computer systems will not require
elaborate water-cooling systems. This will make them better suited to
today's networked computer systems, and more cost competitive.
To further offset declining sales, Unisys is now focusing increasingly upon
the services side of the computer business, providing systems integration
and consulting services to its customers.
The contrasting fortunes of the leading US large and mid-range computer
systems companies are mirrored in the personal computer sector where Compaq
Computer is growing rapidly while Apple Computer is struggling to maintain
profitability and IBM's PC operations appear to be faltering after a strong
comeback in 1993.
Compaq Computer reported 'unprecedented demand' for its PC products in 1993
and set a goal of becoming the world PC market leader by 1996, overtaking
IBM and Apple Computer. Compaq's 1993 revenues jumped 75 percent to Dollars
7.2bn. Net income more than doubled to Dollars 462m.
'We feel very much like the market leader,' said Eckhart Pfeiffer, Compaq
president and chief executive. 'We have mapped out our strategy and I
believe that we can get there.'
According to market analysts at International Data Corporation (IDC), Compaq
may achieve its goal even sooner. In terms of unit shipments, Compaq led IBM
and Apple in the first quarter of 1994, according to IDC's preliminary
estimates.
The market research group estimates Compaq's unit shipments in the first
quarter at 970,000, up 40 per cent from the same period last year. Apple
shipped about 845,000 Macintosh PCs in the first quarter, an increase of
eight percent year to year, maintaining its second place position in the
market.
IBM, however, dropped to third place with shipments of about 840,000 PCs
worldwide in the first quarter, up six percent from the same period last
year, but 48 percent lower than in the fourth quarter of 1993.
Compaq has become the model PC company, which competitors aim to emulate.
The secret to Compaq's success, says a senior executive at one of its
competitors, is that the company 'has perfectly interpreted the new style of
computing.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
