<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / Survey of German Banking and Finance (1): Frankfurt's role
consolidated - Many foreign institutions have boosted their Frankfurt
operations. Meanwhile, pressure for reform of the financial system is
mounting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last year's decision to site the future European Central Bank in Frankfurt
consolidated the city's position as one of Europe's leading financial
centres.
Despite this decision, few German bankers would dare suggest today that the
Frankfurt Finanzplatz will grow in stature to the point where it will become
the financial centre for Europe, knocking London off the pedestal which it
has traditionally occupied.
'It isn't really a question of eclipsing London,' commented Mr Herbert
Jacobi, chief executive of Trinkaus &amp; Burkhardt, the Dusseldorf-based bank
owned by Midland Bank of the UK. 'In the long term, the likelihood is that
we will have two strong financial centres for Europe.'
Even this prognosis would have sounded hopelessly optimistic a few years ago
when the German financial markets were renowned for being small,
overregulated and hostile to innovation. 'New ideas would travel their way
slowly from Wall Street to the city of London and then across to Amsterdam
and Luxembourg before they would finally filter into the German market,'
observes one banker.
Relative to Germany's standing as Europe's leading industrial power, the
country's financial system seemed unsophisticated and underdeveloped.
Outsiders gleaned the impression that the big commercial banks, which
dominate the German financial markets, were content to leave it this way.
The strength of the D-Mark and of the economy were matched by a robust
banking sector, quashing any latent calls for reform.
'But there is a growing awareness that if the German financial system wants
to become a major player in world markets - to compete effectively in debt
and equity markets - it has to adopt international standards on a variety of
issues, ranging from rules on insider trading to increased transparency for
shareholders,' said the chief executive of the Frankfurt arm of a US
investment bank.
'Up until recently I got the distict impression that these sort of things
were not taken at all seriously in Germany.'
The pressure for reform of the Finanzplatz - embracing the regulatory
environment, the structure of the financial markets as well as relations
between company management and shareholders - has come from a number of
different directions. The factors include:
The shock induced by the near-collapse of Metallgesellschaft, the
Frankfurt-based industrial group which came to the brink of bankruptcy in
January, has been amplified by the failure of the Jurgen Schneider property
group in April this year.
In both cases the companies had close relationships with Deutsche Bank,
Germany's biggest bank. While the Schneider case raised questions about
Deutsche's lending procedures, the Metallgesellschaft debacle raised
questions about the system of 'corporate governance' prevailing in Germany.
Metallgesellschaft is owned by some of the most reputable companies in
Germany, including Deutsche Bank, Dresdner Bank, the Allianz insurance group
and Daimler-Benz. Their representatives sat on Metallgesellschaft's
supervisory board, formally entrusted with the supervision of management,
but they signally failed to see the crisis coming.
While German bankers say that what happened at Metallgesellschaft pales into
insignicance compared to abundant scandals in the UK and the US since the
late 1980s, the affair raised questions about Germany's two-tier board
system and the cross-holdings between big German companies, provoking calls
for greater transparency in company affairs in order to protect the
interests of shareholders at large.
A second factor is the German recession combined with the costs of
reunifying eastern and western Germany. The government is running a large
budget deficit which it intends to eliminate in part via privatisations.
Bonn officials recognise that steps must be taken to improve German
financial markets in order to ensure that the coming sale of stakes in
Lufthansa and Deutsche Telekom can be effected smoothly and at the best
price.
Germany's equity markets are underdeveloped by international standards: only
6 per cent of German households own shares, compared to more than 20 per
cent in the UK and the US. The market capitalisation of German shares
equated to about 30 per cent of Germany's GNP at the end of last year,
compared to more than 60 per cent in the US and Japan and more than 100 per
cent in the UK. There are only 665 listed companies in Germany, compared to
more than 2000 in the UK alone. In Germany there have been approximately 200
new issues in the past decade, compared to 180 in the UK last year alone.
Germany is now a net importer of capital, rather than an exporter. It
imported DM186.5bn of long-term funds last year. As yet, this has had little
direct impact on the corporate sector, where companies are relatively liquid
and deferring important investment decisions until the upturn in Germany is
established.
But German companies will have to turn to foreign investors for finance when
the upturn is under way, forcing them to adapt themselves to the needs of
fund managers in the US, the UK and Asia, who will demand greater financial
information than German corporates are ready to disclose. The clearest
example of what is likely to develop into a trend is Daimler-Benz's move to
obtain a full listing on the New York Stock Exchange last autumn, a
precursor to a big rights issue scheduled for later this year.
International investors already exert growing influence as owners of German
shares. In 1990 - the last time the Bundesbank prepared statistics - they
owned 14 per cent of the market. This is almost half the 'free-float' in the
shares of Germany's tightly held quoted companies.
International competition in the securities markets. London's
telephone-based Stock Exchange Automated Quotation System succeeded in
gaining significant market share in the turnover of leading German equities.
Data on this is imprecise, but Mr Werner Seifert, chief executive of the
Deutsche Borse, the German stock exchange, said recently that London had a
10 per cent share of trading in Germany's leading shares - a market share
which Seifert denounced as 10 per cent too much.
Competition is nakedly evident in the battle between the London
International Financial Futures Exchange (Liffe), London's futures and
options exchange, and the Deutsche Terminborse, Germany's screen-based
equivalent.
The DTB was set up in 1990 directly to counter the threat that Liffe would
drag business in German government securities and related derivatives
products to London. Liffe still dominates the market for the key Bund future
contract with a 70 per cent market share but the DTB has challenged Liffe on
other D-Mark products.
In equities, Germany has become conscious that its international competitive
position could be threatened by the fragmentation of liquidity between seven
separate stock exchanges. The creation of the Deutsche Borse last year was
designed to pool investment and technological resources between the
exchanges.
The government has responded to the above pressures for reform by promoting
the second Finanzmarktforderungsgesetz, Financial Markets Promotion Act.
This will make insider dealing a criminal offence and introduce a new
regulatory framework for the German securities industry.
For its part, the Bundesbank has gradually relaxed its opposition to
financial liberation. For example, it allowed the DTB to come into being and
more recently it has reduced its minimum reserves requirements - obliging
banks to lodge interest-free deposits with the central bank - and relented
after years of opposition to money market funds.
These measures alone do not make a Finanzplatz: critics argue that the
hierarchical structure of the big German banks hinders financial innovation.
Moreover, Frankfurt, however convenient a place to live, does not have quite
the same draw for international financial executives as London or New York.
But the backwardness of the German financial markets in comparison to the
size of the economy represents a powerful business argument for being in
'Mainhattan'.
Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, Merrill Lynch, Kleinwort Benson, Mees Pierson
and Caisse des Depots are among the many foreign institutions which recently
boosted, or have recently announced plans to boost their Frankfurt
operations.
</TEXT>
