<PROFILE>_AN-EE4DFAECFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940531
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / International Bonds: Traders braced for supply of long-dated
state debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
European government bonds drifted sideways in thin volume and eurobond
issuance ground to a halt as UK and US markets were closed for national
holidays.
However, supply looms large this week, with several markets preparing to
absorb long-dated government bond issuance.
The Bundesbank is expected this week to announce the German government's
first 10-year bund since last September, which is expected to be issued
within the first 10 days of June and seen totalling around DM10bn.
Meanwhile, after selling L4,000bn of three and five-year notes yesterday,
Italy plans to issue another L5,500bn of seven-, 10 and 30-year paper.
In addition, France is to issue FFr20bn, which most traders expect to be
raised via a new 10-year benchmark, while Sweden's National Debt Office
yesterday called for bids for Friday's auction of SKr3bn of 20-year
index-linked bonds.
Continuing uncertainty in the US market is also likely to weigh on the
markets, with traders nervously eyeing Friday's release of the latest US
jobs data.
All this is expected to lead to further yield curve steepening in Europe,
with investors still unwilling to commit funds to the longer-dated
instruments.
After last week's losses, German government bonds posted small gains
yesterday. The June bund futures contract on DTB rose 0.13 point to 93.60.
Bundesbank officials last week indicated that their securities repurchase
rate could continue declining even if cuts in official rates remain on hold
for now, so dealers this week will be watching the German central bank's
latest repo operation for an indication of continued easing.
'If they lower the repo rate by five basis points, that would allow the Bank
of France to cut (its intervention rate) by 10 basis points on Thursday,'
said Mr Steve Major, head of bond research at Credit Lyonnais in Paris.
The French central bank left its intervention rate unchanged at 5.40 per
cent yesterday.
Moody's Investors Service has lowered the Canadian Province of Ontario's
long-term debt rating to Aa3 from Aa2, matching Standard &amp; Poor's
downgrading to AA- from AA in November.
The move followed a review of the province's financial and debt outlook and
reflects the fact that Ontario's budgetary imbalance is likely to remain
sizeable and wider than forecast.
Moody's added that debt levels will continue rising rapidly given the
anticipated requirements needed to fund the deficit and increasing
non-budgetary spending.
In addition, next year's provincial election and growing debt servicing
costs could affect the pace of fiscal recovery in the next few years.
The Hellenic Republic announced on Friday it has awarded the mandate for its
Dollars 500m syndicated loan to a group of banks led by NatWest and
Mitsubishi Bank.
Following last week's downgrading of Greece by Moody's to Baa1 from Baa3,
some bankers say the all-in price may have to be above initial indications
of around 110 basis points above Libor, closer to 120 over.
From June 1, Irish government bonds will be accepted for custody, clearance
and settlement in the Cedel system. Cross-border settlement between a Cedel
customer and a counterparty in the Irish market will be possible against
payment in Irish pounds through Citibank Dublin, the Cedel depositary in
Ireland.
The Cedel system now includes links with 18 domestic markets and, with the
inclusion of Ireland, government bonds from 13 European countries are now
eligible in the system.
Internationale Nederlanden Bank has established a Dollars 3bn euro
medium-term note programme, arranged by Merrill Lynch, which will facilitate
issuance denominated in a variety of currencies, the bank said.
</TEXT>
