<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / International Company News: CSR rises 40% and forecasts
further advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CSR, the Australian building products, aluminium and sugar group, yesterday
reported a 40 per cent increase in profits after tax but before abnormals to
ADollars 296.5m (USDollars 212m) during the year to end-March.
CSR, which reported trading gains from all its main divisions and forecast a
continued profit improvement in the current year, said the advance was
reached on revenues up by 16 per cent, at ADollars 5.36bn.
The progress translated into earnings per share of 33.6 cents, compared with
25.1 cents in the previous 12 months (before abnormals).
The company incurred no abnormal charges in the most recent 12 months, but
suffered a ADollars 35.1m item in 1992-93, leaving profits after tax and
abnormals in that year at ADollars 231.3m.
The biggest divisional improvement came in the timber operations, where
operating profits jumped to ADollars 71.3m from ADollars 28.8m.
The core building and construction materials business saw profits of
ADollars 241.4m against ADollars 226m, while the North American construction
materials division made ADollars 106.3m compared with ADollars 79.1m.
CSR said it expected demand in its domestic market to remain close to
current levels this year. It acknowledged that Australia's house building
improvement might ebb, but suggested that commercial construction should
recover.
The aluminium division saw operating profits rise to ADollars 76.4m from
ADollars 41.5m, largely due to falling production costs. CSR said it was
surprised by the recent rise in aluminium prices. Because of the high level
of world stocks, it did not expect a significant recovery in price levels
until 1995.
The sugar division made a profit of ADollars 127.7m against ADollars 118.6m.
CSR said it expected 1994 raw sugar production to reach record levels. But
it said longer-term prospects for the Australian refined sugar industry were
less encouraging, with persistent oversupply.
CSR said it was retaining a ADollars 40m reserve against asbestos-related
claims, though it suggested legal developments in the US had generally been
favourable.
</TEXT>
