<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / International Company News: Suez in property deal with
Unibail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Suez, the French financial and industrial holding company, is selling a
large part of the property assets of its Compagnie Fonciere Internationale
property subsidiary to Unibail, the property management group, for between
FFr3.2bn and FFr4bn (Dollars 570m to Dollars 712m).
The deal forms part of the long-term strategy of asset sales adopted by
Suez, which has for the past two years been rationalising its labyrinthine
web of interests and is expected within the next few weeks to finalise
negotiations to sell Victoire, its insurance business.
Suez said it expected to make a capital gain of between FFr1.5bn and
FFr1.9bn on the CFI deal, which includes the sale of a number of commercial
centres, offices and residential property developments.
Yesterday's announcement followed months of talks with Unibail and other
prospective purchasers.
Mr Leon Bressler, chairman of Unibail, said the acquisition offered 'a rare
opportunity' for his company to expand its commercial centre interests.
Unibail will help finance the transaction with the proceeds of its recent
FFr1.25bn convertible bond issue.
'For the past two years we've pursued a policy of investing in commercial
centres, as it is an area of the French property market that has
traditionally been neglected,' said Mr Bressler. 'It isn't very often that a
large portfolio of commercial properties like this becomes available in
France.'
Unibail already has interests in a number of large commercial centres,
notably in the Paris region. It has made several acquisitions in the field
over the past two years, culminating late last year in its purchase of a
number of retail properties from the Pinault-Printemps group.
Meanwhile Suez, which over the past two years has raised FFr20bn from asset
sales, is trying to conclude negotiations to sell Victoire, which is valued
in its books at around FFr18bn. Victoire has been up for sale since last
autumn when Suez ceded control of its German interests to Union des
Assurances de Paris.
Mr Gerard Worms, chairman, last month announced that Suez had received four
offers for Victoire and that it would decide which to accept by the end of
June. The potential purchasers are believed to include Italy's Generali,
Commercial Union of the UK and AEG of the US.
Suez yesterday said the Victoire talks were proceeding smoothly and that it
was still on course to conclude the deal by the end of next month.
</TEXT>
