<DATE>940531
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAY 94 / International Company News: Former PM given Mondadori board
seat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Silvio Berlusconi, Italy's prime minister, yesterday took further steps
to distance himself from his business interests by appointing a respected
Italian parliamentarian to the board of Mondadori, the publishing company he
intends to float on the Milan bourse.
However, at the same time, it was revealed that Mr Pier Silvio Berlusconi
and Ms Marina Berlusconi - the prime minister's two grown-up children from
his first marriage - had been given seats on the board, indicating that the
media magnate has no intention of abandoning ultimate ownership of his stake
in the group.
The appointment of Mr Giovanni Spadolini, a Republican senator and former
prime minister, is intended as a guarantee, if only symbolic, that Mr
Berlusconi will keep his political and publishing interests apart. Mr
Spadolini stood against Mr Berlusconi's candidate in last month's election
for speaker of the senate, and lost by only one vote.
A handful of the media magnate's close political and business associates
have stepped down from the Mondadori board ahead of flotation, which is
likely to take place in July.
The company said its chairman, Mr Leonardo Mondadori, had asked Mr Spadolini
to become a director 'as a guarantor of the cultural continuity and of the
independence of the publishing house'.
At the moment, only 2 per cent of Mondadori is quoted on the Milan stock
exchange.
Mondadori has now merged with Silvio Berlusconi Editore, the private company
which holds the prime minister's other publishing interests, and yesterday's
board meeting formally approved the plan to float up to 53 per cent of the
company. The roadshow for the sale will begin tomorrow.
Mr Franco Tato, Mondadori's chief executive, revealed at yesterday's meeting
that the combined company would have shown a gross operating profit of
L252bn (Dollars 149m) in 1993, on sales of L1,830bn.
</TEXT>
